<HEADLINE> Kuril Islands High on Agenda of Russian-Japanese Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The disputed Kuril Islands was
among the top items discussed here Saturday by Russian and
Japanese foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
"The territorial question was obviously discussed as an
integral part of a peace treaty," Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov told reporters after his talks with his Japanese
counterpart, Masahiko Komura.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said the issue "should be settled without damaging
Russia's sovereignty and territorial integrity."
</P>
<P>
Komura arrived here Friday night on a trip designated to make
preparations for Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's upcoming
state visit to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The visit, scheduled for November 10-13, will be the first
official state visit to Russia by a Japanese Prime Minister in 25
years.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi's predecessor, Ryutaro Hashimoto made informal visits to
Russia earlier. Hashimoto last visited Moscow in mid-September as
advisor to Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
The two sides on Saturday formulated "general points of a
Moscow declaration" to be signed at the November summit, Ivanov
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Saturday meeting, the first between the new Russian
and Japanese Foreign Ministers after the change of cabinets in
both countries, was marked by "good will, trust and openness."
</P>
<P>
The two sides decided that the Japanese and Russian deputy
foreign ministers would hold the next session of the peace treaty
sub-commission in Tokyo on October 29-30, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It was also agreed that the Russian Chief of Staff would visit
Japan in November, and that the Russian and Japanese interior
officials would meet in Moscow in December.
</P>
<P>
Besides bilateral relations, the two sides also discussed a
wide range of international issues, such as Kosovo, Afghanistan
and situation on the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Later Saturday, Komura met with Russian First Deputy Prime
Minister Yuri Maslyukov as co-chairmen of the Russian-Japanese
Commission on Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Komura told reporters that he was "very satisfied" with the
talks, which touched on investments, technological cooperation and
technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
"This was a very good meeting devoted to bilateral economic
cooperation. It was a meeting where we understood each other,"
Tass quoted Komura as saying.
</P>
<P>
Komura is scheduled to leave here for Tokyo later Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
