<HEADLINE> U.S.-China Relationship Important to New Century: George Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. President George
Bush said here today that the world has entered a new geopolitical
era, in which U.S.-China relationship will play an increasingly
significant role in shaping and defining the power structures for
the first half of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an audience at Nanjing University, Bush said
U.S.-China relationship possesses great importance, and that "we
can see the vast potential China has to bring this relationship
more into balance in the coming years."
</P>
<P>
Bush is here visiting Nanjing University, which had set up the
Nanjing-Hopkins Center for Chinese and American Studies in 1980s
together with Hopkins University.
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of U.S.-China summit this summer, acknowledging
that the people of both countries saw their leaders engage in a
fascinating exchange which demonstrated that it not only is
possible to address important issues, but also "disagree about
some of them without throwing bilateral relations into a tail
spin."
</P>
<P>
"That in itself is an important measure of how the relationship
is progressing," said the former U.S. president, who has now been
bestowed honorary chairman of the center's advisory council,
adding that "it also is basis on which to build, to be able to
have frank and candid exchanges about important issues,
identifying areas in which the two sides can cooperate, and
understanding not only where there is a difference of views but
also why."
</P>
<P>
"These are the characteristics of a healthy relationship
between two great powers", and "it is a trend which should be
nurtured," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Bush said, more and more people are coming to
appreciate the fundamental impact that the bilateral relationship
will have on peace and security into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing University today held a ceremony of conferring Former
President George Bush with a honorary doctoral degree. 
</P>
</TEXT>
