<HEADLINE> Feature: Annual Sedan Chair Race, Weekend's Hot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Sportswriter Zhou Zongxin
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 17 (Xinhua) -- "It's really an excellent
and exciting race! I feel great as I jogged and finished the
race with my teammates, " said Maggie Renolds.
</P>
<P>
"It does not matter whether we could win. It's for charity
and a lot of fun as well," the 45-year-old member of the Hong
Kong Ladies Hash House Harriers team said at the finish line of
the 24th Matilda Bazaar &AMP; Sedan Chair Race here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Jogging twice a week with other club members, she said the
race was not tough at all for her. She was participating for the
fourth time this year in the race supported by the Matilda
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
Her team had joined three others in the 2.1-kilometer-long
ladies' race, which was eventually won by a team from the Hong
Kong Ladies Road Runners Club. "They (Road Runners) are real
athletes," claimed a member of a losing team.
</P>
<P>
A total of 35 teams competed this year in the charity race,
which race has been held annually since 1975, when a
reconstruction project was completed for the hospital. To
promote the image of the hospital, a sedan chair race was held at
the time, in commemoration of the old-fashioned tool, which was
generally used to transport patients to the hospital when it
began public services in 1907.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Police won the 3.2-kilometer men's Course A title
while Athletic Veterans of Hong Kong (AVOHK) took the Course B
race of 2.1 kilometers on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The annual event raised 2.2 million HK dollars (0.28 million
U.S. dollars) last year for local charities. This year's
fund-raising target is ambitious 3 million HK dollars (0.38
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Under the rules, teams of eight transport a sedan chair around
the course containing, in case of the men, a passenger "over 16
years of age, alive and human." The ladies, however, are allowed
to carry a dummy weighing no less than 25 pounds.
</P>
<P>
Many of the participating teams in Course B put considerable
efforts into decorating their sedan chairs and dressing the team
members in outlandish fancy dress costumes, to entertain
themselves and the crowd.
</P>
<P>
At the Bazaar, there were stalls selling a variety of
merchandise including clothing, wine, toys, plants, Christmas
cards, home-made cakes, and other delicious produce. A stall
with fancy face-painting services available came out the most
attractive for kids while the live performance by girl pipers
from a middle school and by traditional lion dance drew large
crowds and photographers.
</P>
<P>
"I'll be here again next year," six-year-old Tom said while
waiting for his term at the face-painting stall. Holding toys
bought at another stall, his mother smiled by his side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
