<HEADLINE> France Offers Aid to Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 17 (Xinhua) -- France will provide Lesotho
with emergency food aid worth 300,000 Francs (about 56,000 U.S.
Dollars), French ambassador to South Africa Tristan D'albis said in
Pretoria Saturday.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association quoted D'albis as reporting that
the food aid would be channeled through the United Nations' World Food
Program (WFP).
</P>
<P>
"This French contribution targets the WFP food assistance program
for the primary schools in Maseru from October to December 1998,"
the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho, a tiny mountain kingdom in southern Africa, appealed
to the international community for assistance in rehabilitating
the capital of Maseru and other towns which fell victim to
looting and arson during political riots in September.
</P>
<P>
The Lesotho crisis was resulted from allegations from opposition
parties that the May 23 general election was rigged in favor of the
ruling Leostho Congress for Democracy.
</P>
<P>
Following the military intervention by South Africa and Botswana in
the name of the Southern African Development Community in late
September, the situation in the mountain kingdom has become stable.
</P>
</TEXT>
