<HEADLINE> Clinton to Attend Mideast Summit in Maryland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
is flying Saturday to the Wye Plantation, Maryland, to push the
negotiations between the Palestinians and Israelis which made
little progress after two days.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will go by the helicopter Marine One to the venue,
which is 110 km away from Washington, to meet Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The summit is meant to break a 19-month stalemate in the peace
process by nailing down a new transfer of land to the Palestinians
in the West Bank in return for cast-iron Palestinian guarantees
they will crack down on militants.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said some working groups were meeting for a
third day and that Clinton's participation means a new sense of
urgency.
</P>
<P>
The first two days had essentially been a review of positions,
many of which are still far apart, and they were waiting for U.S.
proposals to breathe life into the talks, which Washington wants
to end by Monday at the latest.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said Clinton would have
informal discussions with both Netanyahu and Arafat on Saturday,
but there were no plans at this stage for a three-way meeting.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Clinton pledged to make "intense efforts" over the
weekend. "I'm convinced they're both really trying to bridge the
gaps between them," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
