<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Fund Anti-Poverty Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is to
allocate 203 million Rand (36.25 million U.S. Dollars) for
anti-poverty projects this year, Welfare and Population
Development Minister Geraldine Fraser-Moleketi said Saturday,
International Day for Poverty Eradication.
</P>
<P>
The allocation of the funding will go hand in hand with the
initiative to establish a social development fund,
Fraser-Moleketi told reporters after visiting several
anti-poverty projects in Welkom, about 250 km southwest of
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
"This will be a credit and savings facility for the poorest
section of our society that are not being reached by other
anti-poverty measures," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said it was also imperative that anti-poverty programs
recognized that poor rural communities, with little or no
resources or infrastructure, would be the hardest hit by the HIV
and Aids.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged all South Africans to join hands in the
fight against poverty.
</P>
<P>
South Africa Tuesday launched an 85 million Rand (about 12
million U.S. Dollars) rural anti-poverty project, expecting to
create more than 14,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
Public Works Minister Jeff Radebe said that the money would
also be used to improve among others roads, agriculture, school,
and other facilities in rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
