<HEADLINE> Japan to Give "Regular Payments" on Loan to Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Japan will make "regular
payments" of a 1.5 billion U.S. dollar loan for Russia, a ranking
Japanese official said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Masaki Okada, spokesman for visiting Japanese Foreign Minister
Masahiko Komura, told reporters after Komura's meeting with
Russian First Deputy Prime Minister Yuri Maslyukov that Tokyo
pledged 600 million dollars as the first tranche of the loan
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
About 400 million dollars has already been transferred to
Russia, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Komura, who arrived here Friday night, is on a 24-hour visit
preparing for Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's upcoming
state visit to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Before his meeting with Maslyukov as co-chairman of the
Russian-Japanese Commission for Trade and Economic Cooperation,
Komura also talked with Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov
and Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
Okada said that Ivanov, during his talks with Komura, agreed to
visit Tokyo after Obuchi's Russia visit next month.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi is scheduled to spend November 11 and 12 in Moscow and
November 13 in St. Petersburg, the Interfax news agency quoted
Okada as saying.
</P>
<P>
The program of the visit and the documents being prepared for
the summit, including a so-called "Moscow Declaration", will be
discussed by the two countries' deputy foreign ministers in Tokyo
on October 29-30, Okada said. 
</P>
