<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sea Piracy Escalating Along Nigeria's Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian territorial water
is witnessing unprecedented cases of sea piracy which are
threatening the fishing industry in the West African country.
</P>
<P>
Unless something is done quite fast, the fishing industry in
the country would be paralyzed, an official of fishing industry
here said.
</P>
<P>
N.K. Bhardwai, Managing Director of Ocean Fisheries Limited,
told local newspaper The Guardian that "we all have been gripped
by fear each time our crews venture into the sea" because the
crews have been inundated with stories of piracies.
</P>
<P>
The latest case of piracy experienced by the Dolphine
Fisheries Limited, a joint venture by Nigeria and China, is still
unsettled with the vessel Dolphine IV and its crews being kept as
hostages.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that the crew of Dolphine IV sent SOS signals
for help in the evening of October 5 when they saw armed men in
two powerful speed boats approaching them.
</P>
<P>
When another vessel of the company Dolphine IX which was in
the area responded to their distress call and sped towards them,
the vessel was intercepted by the attackers who started shooting.
</P>
<P>
The armed men engaged Dolphine IX in shooting for half an hour
and the vessel had to speed away while Dolphine IV was
overpowered and "escorted" to Ekini town in Bayelsa State along
the Nigerian coast.
</P>
<P>
According to managers who were sent on October 7 from Lagos to
Ekini town for negotiations, the community who has kept the
vessel as hostage demanded a ransom of 20 million Naira (about
230,000 U.S. Dollars) before the vessel could be freed.
</P>
<P>
Sources of fishing industry noted that this is just a tip of
the iceberg, quoting the President of the Nigerian Trawler Owners
Association, Olubunmi Elliot, as saying that the problem
escalated within the past two months.
</P>
<P>
According to him, on August 19, a vessel was attacked by the
pirates who demanded for a sum of 490,000 Naira (about 5,500
Dollars) in cash.
</P>
<P>
On August 31, another vessel was attacked by Forupa villagers
in Bayelsa State who had kept the vessel for two weeks. The
community demanded for a sum of 300,000 Naira (about 3,500
Dollars) for their elders and the same amount for youths and
other things.
</P>
<P>
On the situation of sea piracy, Martins Anetekhai, Professor
of Fisheries, was quoted as saying that "once they signal your
vessel to stop and it does not stop, they open fire on it. And
if you stop and they take over, your vessel is piloted to the
creek."
</P>
<P>
According to him, the situation could lead to the stoppage of
sea fishing in Nigeria and about 50,000 tons of fish for local
consumption annually would drop drastically.
</P>
<P>
The export of sea foods such as shrimps, prawn and crabs which
earn the country more than 20 million Dollars annually would be
severely affected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
