<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Group Urges Lift of Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 17 (Xinhua) -- A visiting U.S. humanitarian
group Saturday condemned the sustained U.N. sanctions against Iraq
and called for an end to them.
</P>
<P>
The Chicago-based group, called Voices in the Wildness, said at
a press conference that the sanctions violate human rights and
international norms, and are tantamount to crimes of genocide.
</P>
<P>
"The sanctions on Iraq is a new Hiroshima and should be put to
an end as soon as possible," said the group, whose members have
visited Iraq many times.
</P>
<P>
During World War II, the U.S. dropped atomic bombs on two
Japanese cities of Hiroshima and Nagazaki, killing tens of
thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
Michael Gabreal, member of the organization, said she visited
hospitals in Baghdad and two southern cities of Basra and Missan,
seeing that they are in severe shortage of medicine and medical
equipment and many child patients are obviously suffering from
malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions have also caused a lack of stationery for pupils,
she said.
</P>
<P>
Kelley Guerefiel, another member of the group, criticized the
support of the U.S. mass media for Washington's anti-Iraq foreign
policy, saying because of the media's power in misleading, "it is
very difficult for them (group members) to explain the real
situation in which Iraqi people are living to the American people."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed sanctions on Iraq in 1990 following its
invasion of Kuwait, which include a ban on air travel and limits
on sales of oil, the country's main revenue earner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
