<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV/AIDS Deepen Poverty in Developing Countries: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- HIV-related illness and death
deepen existing poverty and increase indebtedness in the
developing countries, the U.N. Development Program (UNDP) has
warned.
</P>
<P>
Coping with the associated health, social and economic impacts
of the epidemic absorbs already scarce resources of the
developing countries, said the UNDP in a report released here
Saturday at a public rally to mark the International Day for the
Eradication of Poverty which fell on October 17.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. agency called on the international community to fully
understand the complex relationship between HIV/AIDS and poverty.
</P>
<P>
Currently around 30 million people worldwide are infected with
HIV/AIDS, including over one million children under the age of
15, most of them are living in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
The report entitled UNDP Poverty Report 1998 further pointed
out that more than 90 percent of the 30 million people are in
developing countries -- particularly in sub-Saharan Africa, which
with only 10 percent of world population, accounts for two thirds
of all HIV infections.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP took Namibia as an example, saying in that country,
AIDS has now overtaken TB and malaria as the number one killer
disease and by the year 2001, the direct medical costs are
expected to consume 13 percent of the Namibian government's
health budget.
</P>
<P>
It, however, praised Uganda and Thailand for their dealing
directly with these issues, and with some success, saying that
the infection levels in the African country has dropped by about
one fifth and that there is continuing evidence of a fall in new
infections in Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
