<HEADLINE> 26 Iranians Released by Taliban Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 17 (Xinhua) -- A group of 26 Iranians released
by the Afghan Taliban militia arrived here Saturday evening, the
official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
These Iranians, mainly truck drivers, were set free by the
Taliban following the mediation of Lakhdar Brahimi, special envoy
of the U.N. secretary general on Afghan affairs.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi has visited Iran, Pakistan and Afghanistan in an effort
to defuse the tension between Iran and the Taliban, triggered by
the killing of nine Iranian diplomats and reporter by the Taliban
forces in August.
</P>
<P>
Iran massed more than 200,000 troops on its eastern border with
Afghanistan to put pressure to bear on the Taliban, the student
militia now controlling 90 percent of the country.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to Kandahar, the Taliban's headquarters in
southern Afghanistan, Brahimi received a promise from the Taliban
leaders to release all Iranian citizens captured in northern
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban earlier accused the Iranians of sending arms to
the opposition, the Northern Alliance led by the ousted President
Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
Iran denied the charges, claimed that the Iranians were
arrested while send commercial goods to Afghan people in need.
</P>
<P>
So far a total of 51 Iranians have been released in five groups
by the Taliban, following the mediation of Pakistan and the U.N..
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said that Brahimi would return to Iran
for further talks with Iranian officials as the Taliban announced
readiness to hold talks with Iran.
</P>
<P>
An Iranian Foreign Ministry official said earlier that Tehran
would not hold talks with the Taliban unless the Afghan militia
release all Iranians captured in Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
