<HEADLINE> Chinese Army Wins Crucial Match to Stay Alive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Army team scored a
crucial victory of 1-0 against Qingdao Hainiu to keep alive their
hope of staying in the top flight of Chinese soccer next season.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Army eleven had collected 26 points from 24 matc
hes before their clash against Qingdao Hainiu. They could have
been dropped to the second division if they failed to win the
match on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
But the young and high-spirited team never gave up their hopes
and played aggressively from the very beginning of the match.
</P>
<P>
Their efforts paid off finally as Pan Yi connected a pass in
the penalty area and beat the Qingdao goal-keeper with a fierce
shot at the 60th minute.
</P>
<P>
After conceding the goal, the Qingdao team suddenly woke up
and began to launch some attacks. But they could not find the
way to tear up the defence of the Chinese Army team.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen Ping'an, which is also on the verge of relegation
zone, had their morale boosted after beating Sichuan Quanxin 4-2
at home. Shenyang Haishi downed Shandong Luneng 1-0 and Wuhan
Hongjinlong defeated Guangzhou Apollo 4-0.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in the five-year-old Chinese professional
league, there are still seven to eight teams on the verge of
relegation with only one round of matches left.
</P>
<P>
Vanguards Huandao, which needed a win on Sunday to secure
their place in the first division, lost to Guangzhou Songri 1-0
and joined Shenyang Haishi, Chinese Army, Shenzhen Ping'an,
Yanbian Aodong and Wuhan Hongjinlong in a desperate fight to keep
their place in the league.
</P>
<P>
Dalian Wanda, which had already won the title, were forced to
a goalless draw by Beijing Guo'an on Sunday. Beijing Guo'an now
place third in the league, four points behind Shanghai Shenhua.
</P>
<P>
The last round of matches is scheduled next Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
