<HEADLINE> Rehabilitation Program to Benefit More Disabled Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 18 (Xinhua) -- About three million disabled
people across China will benefit from a large-scale rehabilitation
program in the next two years, according to the China Disabled
Persons Federation (CDPF) today.
</P>
<P>
The total number of people who recover from disabilities to one
extent or another will reach six to seven million by then.
</P>
<P>
The three million people will include 1.2 million cataract
patients, 350,000 crippled people, 60,000 deaf-mute children,
60,000 mentally retarded children, and 1.2 million people with
serious mental disorders.
</P>
<P>
The CDPF is making efforts to expand a national network
providing rehabilitation training courses and services. This
network is based on families of the disabled and rehabilitation
centers in residential communities, said Sun Jinzhong, deputy
director of the CDPF's rehabilitation department.
</P>
<P>
All cataract surgeries will be accomplished by "Sight First China
Action," a project launched by the Ministry of Health,
the CDPF and Lions Clubs International last year, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to complete 1.75 million surgeries within five
years. By the year 2001, China's ophthalmologists will be able to
perform 450,000 such surgical procedures annually, and curb the
climbing incidence of cataracts, he said.
</P>
<P>
The CDPF plans to develop and supply 2.4 million special
pieces of equipment and devices for the purpose of rehabilitation and
to aid people with disabilities in their daily lives.
</P>
<P>
Sun also stressed the CDPF's plan to help people with serious
mental disorders to live normal lives as ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
"We'll try to relieve them through medical and psychological
therapies, and help them become accepted gradually by the rest of
society," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
