Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), but Damascus has denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz said recently that Turkey
would take decisive measures if Syria continues to support the
PKK which has been fighting for autonomy in southeast Turkey
since 1984.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Friday, the Turkish Foreign Ministry
rejected an offer from Syria for wide-range talks with
Turkey, saying what concerns Ankara now is only the issue of
Kurdish rebels. 
