<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Conference on Disabled Draws Global Attention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing Third National
Congress of the China Disabled Persons Federation in Beijing
has drawn extensive attention from the international community.
</P>
<P>
The General Secretary of the United Nations Kofi Annan, the
Executive Secretary of the Economic and Social Commission for Asia
and the Pacific (ESCAP) Adrianus Mooy and heads of several
international organizations for disabled people have sent letters
of congratulations to the congress.
</P>
<P>
"This important meeting addresses a key issue that affects more
than 500 million men, women and children around the world," said
Kofi Annan in a note of congratulations. He offered his best wishes
for "a successful meeting that helps the Chinese people to build a
society in which every citizen can participate fully and actively."
</P>
<P>
The UN General Assembly has adopted the World Program of Action
Concerning Disabled Persons and the UN Standard Rules on
Equalization of Opportunities for Persons with Disabilities, which
represent "political and moral commitments by Member States to
enhance disability prevention, to improve rehabilitation and other
services, and to fight against prejudice," said Annan, adding that
China has joined the drafting of the two documents and has been
actively involved in their implementation.
</P>
<P>
The China Disabled Persons Federation (CDPF), the largest of
its kind in the world, has gained special consultative status with
the UN Economic and Social Council for its outstanding work in
promoting the cause of the disabled in the Asian-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
China has made tremendous efforts in raising public
awareness of the overall situation and the basic human
rights of the 60 million Chinese people with disabilities, said
Kerstin Leitner, UN resident coordinator in China.
</P>
<P>
"As a result of deliberate interventions by the Chinese
government, the CDPF, and the society at large, many disabled
people are actively participating in and benefiting from programs
promoting equal rights for them in the areas of education,
employment, poverty alleviation, rehabilitation and other social
and cultural activities," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I am deeply impressed by your outstanding work in helping the
disabled, especially the blind and people with sight defects, to
achieve economic independence, individual development and freedom,
said Euclid Herrie, president of the World Blind Union during a visit
to China in June.
</P>
<P>
According to the CDPF, the president of Inclusion
International, which helps mentally retarded people to join the
society and enjoy a normal life, and the president of
Rehabilitation International, have also sent letters of
congratulations to the congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
