<HEADLINE> Turkey, Syria to Hold Talks to Ease Tensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem said here Sunday that Turkish and Syrian high-ranking
officials plan to hold security talks in the coming days in a bid
to ease tensions between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency quoted Cem as saying
that Turkey would explain what to be discussed during the
would-be talks.
</P>
<P>
He said earlier that the Turkish-Syrian talks would take place,
but gave no fixed place and time.
</P>
<P>
Cem said that "during the talks (between Turkey and Syria), our
representatives will assess how well Turkey's demands over the
settlement to separatist terrorism are being met."
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Syria of backing Turkey's outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), but Damascus has denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz said recently that Turkey
would take decisive measures if Syria continues to support the
PKK which has been fighting for autonomy in southeast Turkey
since 1984.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Friday, the Turkish Foreign Ministry
rejected an offer from Syria for wide-range talks with
Turkey, saying what concerns Ankara now is only the issue of
Kurdish rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
