<HEADLINE> Iraqi Vice President Meets with Turkish Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Vice President Taha
Yassin Ramadan met Sunday with Turkish State Minister Mehmet
Batalli on enhancing bilateral trade cooperation, the Iraqi News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan asked Batalli to convey an oral message to Turkish
Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz on bilateral relations and the
importance of developing the ties in the interests of the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
Batalli said that his visit shows Turkey's keenness on finding
new means of developing economic and trade cooperation between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that his country has suffered huge economic losses due
to the crippling U.N. economic sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkey says that it has lost more than 30 billion U.S. dollars
worth of business with the neighbor.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council imposed the sanctions on
Iraq, banning export of oil, its main revenue earner, in 1990
after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Batalli voiced confidence that his visit will come up with
positive results and open horizons in the Turkish-Iraqi relations.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish official, leading a trade delegation, arrived here
Friday to attend meetings of the Turkish-Iraqi Joint Committee
for Economic Cooperation. 
</P>
