<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Atmosphere for Cross-Straits Relations Improving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Jiang Zemin, general secretary
of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC),
met Koo Chen-fu, chairman of Taiwan's Straits Exchange Foundation
(SEF), this afternoon, bringing the SEF delegation's visit to the
mainland to a climax.
</P>
<P>
Jiang affirmed Koo's efforts in developing relations across the
Taiwan Straits and expressed his appreciation for the four-point
consensus reached between Wang Daohan, president of the
Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Strait (ARATS), and
Koo Chen-fu.
</P>
<P>
Chinese and overseas media all speak highly of Koo's mainland
tour, and have called the past few days "a week of improving
atmosphere in cross-straits relations."
</P>
<P>
In addition to the four-point consensus, the Taiwan delegation
saw the achievement made on the mainland by the reform and
opening-up drive of the past two decades. Koo had a free exchange
of views with his mainland counterpart during the past few days.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yunlin, director of the Taiwan Affairs Office of the CPC
Central Committee, noted that the specific fruits of the ARATS-SEF
talks will be significant for their contacts and dialogue, and the
improvement of relations across the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
The mainland side has always adopted a positive attitude toward
improving cross-strait relations, and made appropriate
arrangements for Koo's visit.
</P>
<P>
As cross-straits relations is approaching an important historical
moment, the media say that stable and healthy cross-straits
relations for the 21st century will be determined by whether both
sides can hold political negotiations under the one-China
principle as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Qian Qichen, a member of the Political Bureau of the CPC
Central Committee, said in a meeting with Koo that any matter can
be discussed under the one-China principle, including issues of
concern to the Taiwan side.
</P>
<P>
The mainland side has shown its sincerity, say observers,
noting that a new prospect in the development of cross-strait
relations can be expected only if the Taiwan authorities take some
practical steps in realizing peaceful reunification.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
