<HEADLINE> Kuwait Welcomes Egypt's Mediation Between Syria, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait on Sunday welcomed
Egypt's effort to defuse the tension between Syria and Turkey,
saying it hopes the effort will help normalize the Damascus-Ankara
relations.
</P>
<P>
This was expressed during the cabinet's weekly session chaired
by Prime Minister Crown Prince Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Salem
Al-Sabah, the Kuwait News Agency (Kuna) reported.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the ministers were briefed by First Deputy
Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber
Al-Sabah on the letter he received from Egyptian Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa on the mediation of Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak,
according to Kuna.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is employing efforts to defuse the tension through
contacts with Turkish President Suleyman Demirel and Syrian
President Hafez Al-Assad.
</P>
<P>
Tensions were mounting recently between Damascus and Ankara
after they traded accusations against each other, and Turkey
reportedly massed up troops along its border with Syria.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors have long been at odds over issues including
Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), river water
sharing and the Turkish-Israeli military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has accused Syria of harboring the PKK, which has
been fighting since 1984 for an independent Kurdish state in
southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Syria has lashed out at Turkey, a predominantly Muslim
country, for forming a military alliance with Israel, which it
says is targeted against the Arab world, especially itself, and
undermines its bargaining position in negotiations with the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Syria has disputes with Israel over the future of the Golan
Heights, captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war. Damascus
insisted on its return as a condition for peace with the Jewish
state. 
</P>
