<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Few Child Labor Used in Carpet Industry in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Manufacturers attending the
first carpet fair of Nepal here said Sunday that they are now
using good chemical dyes and very few child labor.
</P>
<P>
The use of harmful dyes and that of child labor are partly
blamed for the declining export of completely hand-woven carpets,
Nepal's number one export product, in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
"Ninety-eight percent of chemical dyes and two percent of
vegetable dyes are now used in the carpet industry," said Madhu
Sudan Shrestha from the Brighter Carpet Industries (P) Ltd.
</P>
<P>
He said that the azo-dyes which are harmful to health are now
no longer used, and in his factory, child labor is not used at
all.
</P>
<P>
Rajendra B. Shrestha from the Secretariat of the Nepal Carpet
Mart 1998 which opened here Friday also said that very few child
labor is now used in the industry and only good chemical dyes are
used.
</P>
<P>
He said that to combat the problems of adverse publicity
regarding carpet children, the National Society for Protection of
Environment and Children was established in 1994 and till August
this year, it has rehabilitated 751 carpet children.
</P>
<P>
He said that children aged under 14 are sent back to their
homes for family reunion while the orphaned ones are rehabilitated
at various centers.
</P>
<P>
The society has its own child rehabilitation center where
non-formal education, counseling services and health checkups are
provided.
</P>
<P>
Carpet industry is the biggest sector in the land-locked
country in terms of employment, turnover and foreign exchange
earnings.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that more than 300,000 people are directly and
indirectly employed by the industry.
</P>
<P>
In 1993/94 fiscal year, carpet export amounted to 3.3 million
square meters. But since then, it has declined slowly to 2.8
million square meters.
</P>
<P>
In 1992/93 fiscal year, carpet export earned 164 million U.S.
dollars for Nepal, but by 1997/98, the figure had come down to 125
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In this context, Nepal Carpet Mart 1998 was organized to help
diversify the country's carpet export to new markets and
strengthen its export to traditional markets, which drew 80
percent of the country's exporting strength and some 70
international buyers.
</P>
<P>
The exporters are now targeting the United States, Japan,
Canada, Australia and other European countries except Germany,
where more than 80 percent of the total export goes.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers described the fair as good and successful, saying
that they had good business contacts and interactions at the
three-day event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rosskopf Wins Table Tennis World Cup By Sportswriter Cao Jianjie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, China, October 18 (Xinhua) -- World No. 14 Jorg
Rosskopf outlived a five-set marathon to snatch his first men's
World Cup table tennis title here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old Rosskopf, who brought down China's world No. 2
Kong Linghui and Croatia's defending World Cup champion and world
No. 3 Zoran Primorac in the knockout stages, outlasted South
Korean Kim Taek Soo 21-17, 21-17, 10-21, 21-23, 21-11.
</P>
<P>
Rosskopf booked Sunday's flight to Germany after Wednesday's d
raw, which pitted him against former world No. 1 Jean-Michel
Saive of Belgium, China's Olympic champion Liu Guoliang and
Canada's Johnny Huang in the "Group of Death".
</P>
<P>
He rescheduled his flight after the quarter-final win over
1995 world champion Kong, which he said boosted his ailing morale.
</P>
<P>
After taking the first two sets, Rosskopf appeared slack and
conceded the third set to Kim, hailed as the best penhold topspin
player in the world.
</P>
<P>
There were less swings in the fourth set which went virtually
point for point until Rosskopf missed a backhand hit to face the
deciding set.
</P>
<P>
Rosskopf had a 5-0 run and pulled further away to wrap up the
victory.
</P>
<P>
Rosskopf pocketed the champion's cash award of 38,000
U.S,dollars while Kim got 20,000.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't expect to go so far," said Rosskopf. "I'm not the
best player in the world although I took this title."
</P>
<P>
Kim, who upset Sweden's reigning world champion Jan-Ove
Waldner in the quarter-finals and routed Liu in the semi-finals,
said he was happy with second place.
</P>
<P>
"I couldn't expect more," he said. "I played badly in my group
matches and it was mere luck that sent me into the last eight."
</P>
<P>
Chinese have now regarded Kim as the biggest barrier in their
way to the men's singles title in the Asian Games in December.
</P>
<P>
"I was better than Kim before, but now he holds an upper
hand,"said Liu Guoliang, who has recorded nine wins in his 13
career encounters with the South Korean but lost to him twice in
just over one month.
</P>
<P>
Kim said he would have a shot at the men's singles top honor
in the Bangkok Asian Games. "The gold medal is my goal," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Primorac crushed Liu 21-19, 21-19, 18-21, 21-7 to win
third place and 15,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Rosskopf was the first German to win the World Cup title. In
its previous 18 versions, China has won 10 times, Sweden three,
Croatia twice, Hungary, Poland and France once. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0051 </DOCNO>
