<HEADLINE> China, Portugal to Further Consultations on Macao's Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Both sides of the Sino-
Portuguese Joint Liaison Group (JLG) agreed Monday to continue
their consultations on issues concerning the smooth return of
Macao to China.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued after winding up its 33rd plenary
session here, the JLG said a special working group will be
established in charge of the handover ceremony.
</P>
<P>
During the session held October 13-14, the two sides reviewed
the development of the localization of civil service, the
localization and translation of laws and the use of Chinese as the
official language. They agreed to make further efforts in this
regard, said the communique.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed such topics as after-retirement social
welfare and the transfer of the Macao government's assets, which
are of importance to the smooth handover and future development of
Macao.
</P>
<P>
After further discussions, they agreed to enhance consultations
on the transfer of archives, the nationality issue, franchises
which will expire after 1999, and the structure and transition of
Macao's legal system.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also expressed satisfaction with the consensus
reached between them on more than 80 international conventions
that will remain applicable to Macao after 1999.
</P>
<P>
Consensus was also reached that the trade and cooperation
accord between Macao and the European Communities will remain
effective after December 19, 1999, and on the air service accord
reached between Macao and Laos.
</P>
<P>
Both sides of the JLG described the two-day meeting as being
"friendly and cooperative."
</P>
<P>
The next plenary session is scheduled to start on January 19,
1999 in Macao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
