<HEADLINE> Blair Seeks Solution to N. Irish Arms Impasse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 18 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair would hold urgent talks on Monday with Northern Ireland's
political leaders in an attempt to break the arms decommissioning
deadlock, a government spokesman said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Blair will meet David Trimble, first minister of the Northern
Ireland Assembly, and Sinn Fein's Martin McGuinness separately in
London to discuss measures that will push the peace agreement to
its next stage before the deadline, October 31.
</P>
<P>
Under the Good Friday Agreement weapons are due to be handed in
within two years, but no start date has been specified.
</P>
<P>
However, David Trimble, who is also leader of the Ulster
Unionist party, has refused to implement the agreement further
until the Irish Republican Army (IRA) and other terror groups make
a firm commitment to begin handing over their arsenals.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that the IRA's political wing Sinn Fein cannot be
part of a power-sharing executive until the IRA begins getting rid
of its weapons.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein has said it is not within its power to force the IRA
to give up its weapons at this stage.
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman said the government believes the Nobel Peace
Prize, which was awarded jointly to Trimble and John Hume, leader
of the mainly Catholic Social Democratic and Labour party (SDLP),
may act as a spur to make more progress on the problem.
</P>
<P>
"The Prime Minister will be pressing the issue and seeking to
crack it," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Blair is also due to have discussions with Deputy First
Minister Seamus Mallon of the SDLP later next week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
