Kuwaiti Emir made phone calls to Turkish and Syrian presidents on
the dispute between Ankara and Damascus, urging them to seek
solutions through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
During the call, Emir Jaber asserted to President Demirel that
"dialogue was the best way to resolve tension between the two
Muslim countries, and spare the region a new crisis," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The crisis between Turkey and Syria has been eased after
mediation efforts by Arab leaders, especially Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak who made shuttle visits earlier this month to the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Tensions mounted recently between Damascus and Ankara after
they traded accusations against each other, and Turkey reportedly
massed troops along its border with Syria.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors have long been at odds over issues including
Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), water sharing and
the Turkish-Israeli military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has accused Syria of harboring the PKK, which has been
fighting since 1984 for an independent Kurdish state in the
southeast of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Syria has lashed out at Turkey, a predominantly Muslim country,
for forming a military alliance with Israel, which it says is
targeted against the Arab world, especially itself, and undermines
its bargaining position in negotiations with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Israel is still occupying Syria's Golan Heights, captured in
the 1967 Middle East war. Damascus insisted on its return as a
condition for peace with the Jewish state. 
