<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Pak-Indian Talks End Without Concrete </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Secretary
Shamshad Ahmad and his Indian counterpart K. Ragunath Saturday
ended their three-day peace talks without any concrete progress
but agreed to keep on the dialogue process to find a peaceful
settlement to all the outstanding issues between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement, whose formulation took hours to hammer out
and delayed the departure of the Indian delegation for New Delhi,
merely said the two foreign secretaries would continue their
discussions on issues of peace and security and the Jammu and
Kashmir dispute respectively in the first week of February 1999 in
New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the joint news conference held at the end of the
talks, both Shamshad and Ragunath made it clear that there were no
quick-fix solutions to the long-standing issues including Kashmir
between the two antagonistic neighbors, and the two sides had not
gone into their dialogue with any false or inflated hopes.
</P>
<P>
However, neither side termed the talks, the first of its kind
in more than one year between the two sides, a failure.
</P>
<P>
"We have to be realistic in evaluating the outcome for its
absence. We knew we were just beginning a process and if both
sides show flexibility and comprehension of the present day
situation we could perhaps achieve some progress," Shamshad said.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that these talks "perhaps represented the first
substantial effort in a long time" between the two countries to
address all the bilateral outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
"What is encouraging is that both sides agreed that our
discussions should be guided by a sense of realism and
pragmatism," he added.
</P>
<P>
Indian Foreign Secretary Ragunath endorsed Shamshad's remarks,
saying that "there is no question of the talks having failed, for
the process (of the dialogue) has just started."
</P>
<P>
"There is something that needs to be discussed. The basic
requirement is that we proceed in a realistic and pragmatic
fashion," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, there continued to be fundamental differences in the
way the two sides were approaching the Kashmir issue, which has
bedeviled the bilateral relations between the two countries in the
past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
There are no signs of any change to both sides' known positions
on the Kashmir issue. Pakistan insists that the core issue of
Kashmir should be resolved before any other agreements can be
reached while India favors first taking up commercial and trade
issues, saying the status of Kashmir is not negotiable.
</P>
<P>
"All over the world the trend in such bilateral disputes is for
easier issues to be tackled first rather than the difficult ones,"
Ragunath said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that New Delhi rejects any outside interference
into the bilateral negotiations with Islamabad, saying that "there
is no room for any third party mediation."
</P>
<P>
Apparently the Pakistani foreign secretary did not agree to
such arguments.
</P>
<P>
"The question of third party mediation is not a matter of
principle, it is a matter of necessity whenever it arises," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Bilateralism, he said, is not a principle, "it is a concept
which is developed selectively to suit certain situations."
</P>
<P>
"What happens in South Asia has direct repercussions for other
parts of the world who are naturally interested in this part of
the world," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"This is a reality which nobody can deny - let us not convert
this reality into dogmatic or narrow concept of principles," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, he assured, will address all issues with equal
sincerity and constructive attitude.
</P>
<P>
But, he underlined, given the climate of "mistrust and lack of
confidence" it would be somewhat unrealistic to expect that
substantive progress leading to complete normalization of
relations in all areas can be achieved if the core issue of
Kashmir remains unresolved.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the two countries can begin their journey "by
taking suitable steps in the form of confidence building measures
which will signify our commitment to the reduction of tensions,
non-use of force and peaceful settlement of disputes."
</P>
<P>
The two senior diplomats spent considerable time enunciating
the kind of proposals discussed on the peace and security issues,
especially the confidence building measures in the nuclear and
ballistic fields. Most of these ideas would be worked upon by the
two sides in the talks to be held in New Delhi from November 5 to
13, during which they will take up the remaining bilateral issues
listed on an eight-point agenda agreed upon by them here last
June.
</P>
<P>
The just-concluded talks followed an understanding reached
between Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and his Indian
counterpart Atal Behari Vajpayee in their recent meeting in New
York on the sidelines of the U.N. General Assembly session. Both
leaders underscored the necessity for an environment for durable
peace and peaceful settlement of the Jammu and Kashmir dispute.
</P>
</TEXT>
