<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. African Leaders Call for End to Congo (K) War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Presidents of Kenya, Uganda
and Tanzania called Sunday for the orderly withdrawal of all
foreign troops in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) to speed
up a resolution to the civil war there.
</P>
<P>
The east African leaders, Daniel arap Moi of Kenya, Yoweri
Museveni of Uganda and Benjamin Mkapa of Tanzania, held a one-day
summit in the Kenyan capital here over the Congo war which, they
said, is "threatening to engulf the whole region" of the east and
central Africa.
</P>
<P>
They suggested immediate negotiations involving all parties
over a truce pact and a troop standstill, as well as the
emplacement of a neutral international peace-keeping force under
the auspices of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) and the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they reaffirmed the unity and territorial integrity
of Congo (K), expressing "grave concern" about the impact of the
Congo war on the security of its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
A ministerial-level meeting is expected to be held soon by the
three countries as a follow-up to the summit.
</P>
<P>
The Congo war precipitated "an influx of refugees into
neighboring countries, the displacement of populations, threats
of genocide and decline in trade and investments," they said in a
joint communique issued at the end of the close-door meeting.
</P>
<P>
Congolese rebels scored what appeared to be a major victory
this week in their efforts to topple President Laurent Kabila
when they captured the eastern town of Kindu and its strategic
air base, which government forces had been using to launch
attacks on rebel strongholds in the east.
</P>
<P>
Several countries have been reportedly drawn into the fighting
in Congo (K) since it broke out on August 2. Zimbabwe, Angola,
Namibia and Chad have all acknowledged sending troops to fight on
the side of Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda, although they do not openly admit support
for the rebels, are allegedly providing military and logistical
backing "to defend their legitimate security interests".
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian president and his Zambian counterpart Frederick
Chiluba were appointed last month by the South African
Development Community (SADC) to meet with all parties to the
Congo conflict in an effort to broker peace in Africa's third
largest country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
