<HEADLINE> Howard Promotes Young Talent Into New Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister John Howard
moved to restructure his government for the new millennium Sunday
by reshaping key economic portfolios, dumping three ministers and
promoting some of his party's brightest young talent to the front
bench.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle also resulted in a major promotion for South
Australian Senator Nick Minchin who moves from the junior ministry
into Cabinet as minister for Industry, Science and Resources.
</P>
<P>
Former ministers for the Status of Women Judi Moylan, Regional
Development Alex Somlyay and Tourism Andrew Thomson have been
dropped from the front bench.
</P>
<P>
Another three vacancies were created by the retirement from
politics of Defense Minister Ian McLachlan, the decision by
Resources Minister Warwick Parer to stand down from the ministry
and the election defeat of Family Services Minister Warwick Smith.
</P>
<P>
Filling the vacancies are young Sydney MPs Joe Hockey, Tony
Abbott and Jackie Kelly; former Liberal shadow ministers Senator
Ian MaCdonald from Queensland and Wilson Tuckey from Western
Australia; and Peter McGauran, the National Party minister forced
to quit the front bench last year over the travel rorts affair.
</P>
<P>
Most senior ministers keep their jobs. Deputy Prime Minister
Tim Fischer retains Trade, Peter Costello remains Treasurer,
Alexander Downer remains his job in the Foreign Affairs Ministry
and John Fahey successfully resisted attempts to move him from the
Finance portfolio.
</P>
<P>
The biggest shake-up came in Primary Industries, which has been
broken up with the loss of Resources and Energy to the Industry
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
National Party Deputy Leader John Anderson also ends a troubled
period in the job by shifting to Transport and Regional Services,
the new super ministry for the bush.
</P>
<P>
But the Nationals retain the remnants of the old portfolio with
Mark Vaile taking over the new Ministry for Agriculture, Fisheries
and Forestry.
</P>
<P>
Peter Reith has added Employment to his responsibilities for
Workplace Relations and Small Business at the expense of David
Kemp, who keeps Education and a spot in Cabinet, but pays the
price for the troubled privatization of the Commonwealth
Employment Service.
</P>
<P>
As expected, John Moore moves into Defense, handing his
Industry portfolio over to Nick Minchin, one of two new faces in
Cabinet, and with the added responsibilities of Science and
Resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
