<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Regional Environment Conference Conducive to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, October 18 (Xinhua) -- After five days of extensive
discussions and exchange of views, the 6th General Assembly of the
Asia-Pacific Parliamentarians Conference on Environment and
Development (APPCED) wound up here today with a series of
consensus reached among the participants.
</P>
<P>
The meeting passed the "Guilin Declaration," calling for
governments and parliaments of all countries to promote its
regional sustainable development through bilateral or multilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
It also urged the international community, especially the
developed countries and concerned international organizations, to
give new and additional financial and technical support to
developing countries so their tourist industries can develop in a
sustainable manner.
</P>
<P>
The whole world is concerned with what kind of earth the
mankind will leave to future generations. This issue was also the
focus of discussions at this conference, which was attended by 160
representatives from 27 countries and international organizations,
including 11 parliament leaders.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress, attended the meeting and delivered a speech on
China's environmental protection efforts. Li and vice chairman
of NPC the Standing Committee Zou Jiahua met separately with the
participants at the meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Regional Environment Conference Conducive to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The representatives from other countries also briefed the
conference on their experience in facing the challenge of
environmental protection and promoting the sustainable development
of tourism.
</P>
<P>
China's NPC delegation raised five principles for a sound
relationship between environmental protection and the development
of tourism.
</P>
<P>
These include: actively developing tourism and improving its
quality during the course of development; placing equal stress on
development and environmental protection, rational exploitation
and optimized utilization of tourism resources; strengthening
comprehensive coordination and realizing systematic optimization;
setting up an organizational-guarantee system and creating a
social atmosphere for supporting and promoting the sustainable
development of tourism; having the countries of the Asian-Pacific
region participate equally in international cooperation to avoid
producing harmful effects on other countries in the course of
developing tourist resources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Regional Environment Conference Conducive to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
These principles won recognition from all the attending
representatives, and much of its content was incorporated into the
"Guilin Declaration," approved by the conference today.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, the participants visited the Guilin
Sewage Processing Plant and toured along the 100-kilometer
Lijiang River, enjoying its magnificent sceneries. They saw
firsthand the endeavors and achievements made by Guilin and China
in environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Many of the participants who came to China for the first time
said the beautiful scenery of Guilin greatly impressed them.
</P>
<P>
The "Guilin Declaration," a major fruit of the 6th General
Assembly of the APPCED, is intended to serve as a guideline for
the Asian-Pacific region, and the rest of the world, to enhance
exchange and cooperation in environmental protection and
development.
</P>
<P>
The participants said the publication and endorsement
of the declaration represented the understanding between the
parliaments of the Asian-Pacific region, and will produce
positive effects for environment protection and sustainable
development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
