<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Recession Slows Down Reforms in ASEAN Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Representatives attending a
regional meeting here conceded Sunday that economic recession was
impeding the political and economic reforms in ASEAN member
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Asian Liberals and Democrats Conference
highlighted the note that the financial crisis and economic
downturn have affected the process that ushers member countries of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) towards
transparency in each individual society and the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan said that because of
the prolonged economic crisis, the aspiration to achieve "ASEAN
Vision 2000" which features open societies and the rule of law
might not be realized as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
For countries such as Thailand and Indonesia, the crisis posed
positive results in speeding up political reforms, resulting in
the adoption of a democratic constitution, but in certain
countries the crisis has slowed down the process, he said without
elaboration.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Thailand, the Philippines, Malaysia, Indonesia,
Singapore, Brunei, Vietnam, Myanmar and Laos.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever the individual situation is, ASEAN as a region will
inevitably proceed to the very trend of openness and civil society
through internationalization, (therefore we should start)
discussing how to cooperate to avoid letting the region become a
collection of other bubbles," the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
He added that "if we want a government with stability, we must
open channels to popular participation. Asia must make sure it
emerges from the crisis as a strong, mature and disciplined
region".
</P>
<P>
Philippine congressman Felicito Payumo emphasized commitment to
openness and reform, urging ASEAN countries to stay open and be
more transparent to attract more investment.
</P>
<P>
Abhisit Vejjajiva, minister attached to Thailand's Prime
Minister's Office, said the economic crisis has revealed a lack of
strong political institutions and culture, basic to start real
economic reform in the region.
</P>
<P>
"The next development needs a back up of accountability and
transparency of governments. Public and political education are
challenges facing all democrats and many economies in the region,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He also called on international institutions such as the
International Monetary Fund and World Bank to do their part in
sharing the burden of the crisis with Asian countries concerned.
</P>
</TEXT>
