<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Caste System Change Hindus' Genetic Makeup: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 18 (Xinhua) -- A latest study shows that the
3,000-year-old caste system in India has left its indelible mark
on even the genetic make-up of Hindus, the Indian Express daily
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Lower castes have become genetically different from upper
classes and this difference is wider when the caste disparity is
larger, said the study, jointly conducted by Indian and American
researchers.
</P>
<P>
However, experts said one has to be very careful in drawing
conclusions. The study does not in any way conclude or even
remotely suggest that some castes are "superior" or more
"intelligent" than others because of this inherent genetic
variation that has been created due to social norms.
</P>
<P>
They said that researchers have for long tried to use genes and
blood groups to track differences among Hindu castes but this
study, using unique genetic markers, is one of the first to show
the deep and long-term impact of societal rules on the human
genome.
</P>
<P>
The research team, comprising researchers from Andhra
University in Vishakapatnam, 1,880 kilometers southeast of here,
and the University of Utah in the United States, collected blood
samples from 250 unrelated men from 12 Telugu-speaking people
spanning all castes in northeastern Andhra Pradesh.
</P>
<P>
Analyzing the blood with the latest molecular tests at Andhra
University, they found that in the genetic make-up of Hindus,
there is "great divergence" between the upper and lower castes
than between upper and middle or middle and lower castes.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the "genetic distance" between upper and lower castes
is one and a half times greater than between upper and middle or
middle and lower castes, shows the result of the study, which was
published in the current issue of the British journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
Using unique genetic markers, the study shows that men tend to
"stagnate" within the same castes while women have more "mobility"
between the castes which is probably true reflection of what
happens in the Indian society even today.
</P>
<P>
The research found that men of higher castes do regularly marry
lower caste women but the reverse is still rather rare, reflecting
a common norm of women often marrying into castes higher than
theirs and ascending the social ladder into which they were born.
</P>
<P>
Men of closely ranked castes had higher similarities in the
maternal components but in contrast there were few similarities
between the maternal components of men in the higher caste, the
researchers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
