<HEADLINE> Equities Remain Depressed on Bombay Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Contrary to market
expectations of a rally, equities continued their downward march
on the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) during the week due to
sustained sales by foreign funds and operators' disinterest in
making fresh transactions.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index dropped to 2,832.03 points in the first
two sessions but almost recovered its losses when it closed at
2,890.72 at midweek. However, it fell back to close the week at
2,848.11 as against last weekend close of 2,916.66, netting a loss
of 68.55 points.
</P>
<P>
The national index also dipped by 31.52 points to end the week
at 1,269.53 from last weekend close of 1,301.05.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-200 and the U.S. dollar index were sharply down at the
weekend to 295.66 and 116.40 points compared with last weekend
close of 304.24 and 119.58 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market was badly in need of some
market-friendly measures like an economic package or at least
early announcement on buy-back shares. 
</P>
