<HEADLINE> OSCE Advanced Team Arrives in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRISTINA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- An advance team from the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) arrived
in Kosovo on Sunday to prepare for the coming of 2,000 monitors.
</P>
<P>
The 20-member group was transported in five vehicles to
Pristina, capital of Kosovo province, from Belgrade where they
stayed overnight.
</P>
<P>
"We are here to do the preparatory work for the OSCE
verification mission, and we are set to start our efforts
immediately," John Sandrock, head of the advanced team, told
reporters upon their arrival.
</P>
<P>
He said the OSCE mission will bring in the monitors "as quickly
as possible," but he couldn't give the deadline of the deployment.
</P>
<P>
The monitors will be responsible for checking whether both
sides in the conflict comply with an agreement struck five days
ago between Yugoslav President Milosevic and the U.S. envoy,
Richard Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia is given 10 more days to comply with U.N. demands
and pull out troops from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The unarmed observers will be supplied by the 54 member states
of the OSCE, but the main force is expected to take some weeks to
assemble, another OSCE official said in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
American diplomat William Graham Walker was appointed on
Saturday as head of the new OSCE mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, NATO U-2 surveillance aircraft began flights
over Kosovo on Saturday to check if Yugoslavia is complying with
UN demands to withdraw its forces.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia formally agreed to the NATO flights Thursday as part
of the peace accord signed on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Serb Media Center in Pristina
claimed on Sunday that Kosovo Liberation Army "extremists" had
staged numerous attacks on Serb forces and police stations since
Friday, killing four Serb policemen and wounding several
others. It was the most serious incident this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
