<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Turns Dumping Ground for Second Hand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has become a major
dumping ground of second hand wears in the west African
sub-region and local textile firms are advocating 200 percent
tariff on second hand clothes.
</P>
<P>
An investigation conducted by the Sunday Times revealed that
Gatan-Kowa Market which is situated off the Lagos-Abeokuta
express is the hub of these second hand wears in the country.
</P>
<P>
Traders come from across the country to buy these wears
including children's clothes, men and women's wears of different
kinds, undies and foot wears in large quantities for resale in
various markets all over the country.
</P>
<P>
Gatan-Kowa market is a beehive of activities on Mondays,
Wednesdays and Fridays with sea of heads milling all over the
place making brisk business, according to the investigation.
</P>
<P>
Before the economic down-turn in the country, only the low
income earners patronized the second hand wears and at present
the second hand clothes are used by nearly every body, it noted.
</P>
<P>
The investigation further revealed that the second hand wears
come mainly from Poland, England, Holland and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian Textile Manufacturing Association (NTMA) said
recently that its members had to retrench 114,000 workers this
year as a result of the influx of second hand wears into the
country.
</P>
<P>
NTMA Chairman Victor Eburajolo warned that many more may lose
their jobs unless the Nigerian government increased tariff on
second hand clothes to 200 percent to protect local industry.
</P>
<P>
General Manager of GDM Textiles Manufacturing Company Chief
Adebayo Raji said the large scale smuggling of textile products
has further worsened the problem of the textile industry in
Nigeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
