<HEADLINE> Swiss Defense Minister: It's Time We Come to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 18 (Xinhua) -- "Forty-eight years is too long
a time, it's high time we come to China for it is such an
important country," said Adolf Ogi, the first Swiss defense
minister to visit China since the two countries established
diplomatic ties in 1950.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting between the two defense ministers upon Ogi's
arrival, his Chinese counterpart General Chi Haotian extended a
warm welcome, saying, "We've been waiting for you for a long time."
</P>
<P>
Ogi, also a member of the Swiss Federal Council, said in an
exclusive interview with Xinhua today that his trip has won
unanimous approval from the council and is receiving close
attention from the media at home.
</P>
<P>
He said that Switzerland, in a "rapidly changing world hopes
to pursue its interest in a rising, as well as the largest
developing country, in the world."
</P>
<P>
Despite differences between the two countries -- Switzerland
retains a neutral stance while China sticks to its principles in
handling international affairs -- Ogi pointed out that there are
similarities, taking China's non-alignment policy as an
example. "Thus we hope to increase mutual understanding through
the visit, and to seek exchanges and cooperation with China in
economic, cultural and military areas," said Ogi.
</P>
<P>
Ogi said he was delighted that the trip has given him a rough
picture of economic development in China, as well as China's
attitude toward international and regional issues. "We notice at
the same time that China shows tremendous attention to the
situation in Switzerland and the whole European continent," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of his trip to a military base and China's University
of National Defense, Ogi said he was deeply impressed by the
outstanding individual capabilities, and the strong physique of
the Chinese servicemen. "They are well-trained and
well-disciplined," he concluded.
</P>
<P>
What Ogi most admires, however, is the role the Chinese army
played in the fight against the floods this summer. "Armies in
all countries around the globe are faced with the same task, and
may refer to the Chinese army for their experience."
</P>
<P>
Ogi hailed his meeting with Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji and his
talk with Chi Haotian as "tacit, with no need for warming-up."
"The extremely friendly atmosphere shows that Swiss-Chinese
relations are on the right track and are most likely to have
smoother development."
</P>
<P>
"I feel extremely proud, not only for being the first Swiss
defense minister to visit China in half a century, but also for
kicking off the development of another round of Sino-Swiss
relations," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
