<HEADLINE> Indian, Pakistani Border Troops Stop Exchange of Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Amid reports that India and
Pakistan agreed in Islamabad to reduce the risk of nuclear
conflict, border security forces of the two countries decided to
stop exchange of fire along the international border in Jammu
region to de-escalate tension along the border.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) Sunday quoted a spokesman of the
Indian Border Security Force as saying that the decision was taken
by the commanders of both sides during a meeting at the Octerio
border post in Jammu Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The commanders discussed issues pertaining to firing on
civilian areas in which villagers and cattle were becoming
casualties, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the issue of harvesting crops and putting up
additional bunkers on both sides were also raised during the
meeting. 
