<HEADLINE> The ISF World Gymnasiade Ends in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The '98 International
Schoolsports Federation (ISF) World Gymnasiade concluded here
Sunday afternoon, when 773 athltes from over 30 countries and
rigions joined hand in hand to celebrate the success of their own
sports meet in a party.
</P>
<P>
To spare more time for the boys and girls, as Shanghai vice
mayor Zhou Muyao said, the organizing committee decided not to
stage a closing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The high school competitors from around the world gathered in
Shanghai High School, singing, dancing, playing games and sheding
tears when they knew they might not be able to see each other
until four years later.
</P>
<P>
The 2002 ISF World Gymnasiade, the world students games, will
be held in Poitiers, France.
</P>
<P>
Chinese collected 41 golds to top the medal standings, Italy
finished second with 13 and France third with 10.
</P>
<P>
China's 16-year-old gymnasts Xing Aowei became the
most-crowned athlete in the week-long Gymnasiade by winning six
golds.
</P>
<P>
"The Gymnasiade has proved a great success," vice mayor Zhou
said, "The games have provided students from the world an
opportunity to meet and understand each other."
</P>
<P>
The vice mayor said the Gymnasiade created an atmosphere that
will benefit sports education in schools.
</P>
<P>
"Although fund raising was affected by the floods that hit
many parts of China this summer, we explored all possible funding
channels to meet the needs of the games," Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
The ISF general secretary Defever Raymond declared the closing
of the Gymnasiade.
</P>
<P>
The Gymnasiade was the last major students gathering of this
century and the first of its kind held outside Europe.
</P>
<P>
The games were the biggest international sports meet hosted in
Shanghai after it staged the First East Asian Games in 1993 and
the Eighth National Games in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
