<HEADLINE> Pakistan, India Continue to Discuss Kashmir Next  February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The Foreign Secretaries of
Pakistan and India will continue to discuss the Kashmir dispute
and issues of peace and security in February, 1999, in New Delhi,
a joint statement said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad and his Indian
counterpart K Ragunath agreed that the next round of talks on the
issues of peace and security, Jammu and Kashmir and confidence
building measures respectively and a review of the round will be
held in the first half of February, 1999, in New Delhi, said the
statement issued by the two sides at the end of the three-day
talks here Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two sides held separate meetings on the
agenda items of peace and security including confidence building
measures, and Jammu and Kashmir on the basis of the June 23, 1997,
agreement, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The talks were held "in a cordial and frank atmosphere with in
the framework of the composite and integrated dialogue process ,"
it added.
</P>
<P>
The deliberations between the foreign secretaries were guided
by the shared belief of their prime ministers in their Joint
Statement of September 23, 1998, that an environment of durable
peace and security was in the supreme interest of both countries
and the region as a whole, and that the peaceful settlement of all
out standing issues including Jammu and Kashmir was essential
forth is purpose, the statement pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The talks beginning from Friday apparently ended without any
concrete progress. It was the first formal high-level encounter
between the two South Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Another round of talks will be held in New Delhi from November
5 to November 13 to discuss the remaining bilateral issues of the
eight-point agenda reached by the two countries here last June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
