<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPC Attaches Great Importance to Agriculture, Rural Work (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The 15th Central Committee of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) passed a decision on
agriculture and rural work at its third plenary session held in
Beijing last week.
</P>
<P>
The full text of the "Decision of the CPC Central Committee
on Several Major Issues in Agriculture and Rural Work" was
released today.
</P>
<P>
The decision says that the CPC Central Committee's concern for
agriculture and rural work is based on the following:
</P>
<P>
First, China must achieve a sustained development of
agriculture and rural economy if it realizes the goals for
trans-century development put forward at the 15th National
Congress of the CPC.
</P>
<P>
The decision says, of China's 1.2 billion population, some 900
million live in the countryside, and therefore the issues of
agriculture, rural areas and farmers have an important bearing on
China's reforms, opening up and modernization.
</P>
<P>
Without stability in rural areas, there will be no stability
in the country. Without prosperity for farmers, there will be no
prosperity for all of the Chinese. And, without a modernized
agriculture, there will be no modernization in China's economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPC Attaches Great Importance to Agriculture, Rural Work (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Second, China has obtained great achievements in its reform and
opening up which started in rural areas and spread across the
country. So, summing up the experience in the past two decades is
of important significance for the Party to persist in the policies
adopted since the Third Plenary Session of the 11th CPC National
Congress and to expand China's reforms and development.
</P>
<P>
Third, with the current Asian financial crisis and challenges
from economic globablization, agricultural growth, prosperity of
rural areas and the increase of farmers' purchasing power will
help expand domestic demands, keep the momentum for growth of the
nation's economy, and sharpen China's edge in international
competition.
</P>
<P>
China's basic stance is to make an effort to expand the
domestic market, especially the rural market, while making good
use of overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, in the process from getting enough to eat and wear,
then becoming comparatively better-off, and to modernization,
there are many problems in the economic construction, cultural and
ethical progress, legislation, and grass-roots organizations in
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
In some places, the Party's rural policies have not been
implemented in a good way, leading to slow increases in farmers'
incomes and adversely affecting their enthusiasm in farming.
</P>
<P>
Poor agricultural infrastructure and a limited ability to deal
with natural disasters have been blamed for the greater pressure
on the people, resources and the environment.
</P>
<P>
And, it is only when these problems are solved that full
economic development and social progress in rural China can be
achieved and a new socialist, wealthy, democratic and
civilized countryside built. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ragunath: India for Pragmatic Talks With Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Indian Foreign Secretary K.
Ragunath Sunday emphasized that Islamabad and New Delhi should
address all the outstanding issues between the two countries in a
"realistic and pragmatic fashion".
</P>
<P>
Ragunath was talking to reporters at a joint news conference
with his Pakistani counterpart at the end of three days of
exclusive talks on issues relating to peace and security and Jammu
and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
He said the two sides reiterated their positions on the Kashmir
issue in their talks Saturday devoted specifically to the thorny
Jammu and Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
In order to address this long-running dispute in a serious and
substantive manner, Ragunath said there is a need for
"identification of the basic causes and methods" to tackle this
problem.
</P>
<P>
"This is something that needs to be discussed. The basic
requirement is that we proceed in a realistic and pragmatic
fashion," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Let's have a proper assessment of the situation that should be
done in a friendly manner," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Indian delegation has given some proposals on
Kashmir issue to their Pakistani counterparts. But, he did not
elaborate on that.
</P>
<P>
"We should identify the steps needed to move into a meaningful
discussion which will lead to a mutually acceptable solution," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the discussion on peace and security, the Indian
official said this "requires maintaining of peaceful and security
environment which in turn requires improving trust and
confidence."
</P>
<P>
He said the Indian side had put forward a broad package of
proposals on confidence building measures ranging from avoiding of
nuclear conflict to measures for developing secure and dedicated
communication links between political, civilian and military
authorities of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Indian delegation, he said, also proposed the measures
relating to exchange of data, information which could contribute
to greater confidence.
</P>
<P>
The broad subjects which formed the basis for the Indian
proposals, he said, were exchange of views on security concept and
nuclear doctrine, nuclear and conventional confidence building
measures, increase of information exchange leading to greater
transparency and predictability. 
</P>
