<HEADLINE> Lion Kills 30 Cattle in Zambian Village </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- More than 30 head of cattle
have been killed recently by a lion in Siavonga, 200 kilometers
</P>
<P>
Two honorary game scouts based at Gwabi near the affected area
have reportedly abandoned their mission of hunting down the lion
after seeing its big paw prints, fearing it could be
extraordinary and more dangerous, according to the Sunday Times
of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The two have since called for reinforcement from a trained
game scout, who has been operating in another area of Siavonga,
where wild elephants are terrorizing villagers.
</P>
<P>
Chief Sikongo of Siavonga is worried that human life will be
lost if no immediate action is taken.
</P>
<P>
He said poverty among villagers will increase following the
loss of their cattle.
</P>
<P>
People in the two areas terrorized by the lion and elephants
have abandoned field preparations for the forthcoming planting
season beginning next month and children also abandoned school
for fear of the beast.
</P>
<P>
The chief called on the office of the country's vice-president
to send food to the areas where food supplies have run out.
</P>
<P>
He said most families are going without meals prompting him to
make the appeal for relief food, some of which could be sold at a
subsidized price to make it affordable to the villagers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
