<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Makes Public Policies for Agricultural, Rural Development (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, October 18 (Xinhua) -- China today made public ten
policies for agricultural and rural developments from now to the
year 2010.
</P>
<P>
These polices, contained in the "Decision of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) on Several Major
Issues in Agriculture and Rural Work" which was released
today, are as follows:
</P>
<P>
First, China should always give first priority in the
development of national economy. Agriculture is the foundation of
national economy, and its vigorous development will meet the
demand of the lives of the people and guarantee the development
of industry and the service trade.
</P>
<P>
China should adjust national income distribution and increase
input in agriculture. Agricultural legislation and enforcement of
the laws related should be enhanced.
</P>
<P>
Second, China should, in a long period of time, stabilize its
basic policies for rural areas. It should adhere to the basic
economic system in which the major form of public ownership and
other forms of ownership develop simultaneously, to the management
system which combines unified and seperate operations based on the
household contract responsibility, and to the distribution system
which combines incomes from one's work mainly and those from the
essential factors of production.
</P>
<P>
Rural reforms should continue in accordance with the demands
of a socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
Third, China should grasp firm grain production and develop
actively a diversifed economy. While continuing to boost grain
production, the country should adjust the industrial structure in
its rural areas by simultaneously developing agriculture,
forestry, animal husbandry, sideline products and fisheries to
ensure an ample supply of farm produce and a steady increase in
farmers' incomes.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, China should develop agriculture through science and
education. The way out for agriculture lies in science, technology
and education. Agricutrural and rural developments should be
obtained by combining agro-science and education, widely applying
the achievements in agro-scientific research, and training
qualified farmers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Policies for Agricultural, Rural Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fifth, China should achieve a sustained development in
agriculture. It should facilitate construction of water
conservancy projects, speed up afforestation, protect farmland,
forests and water resources, and control soil erosion,
desertification and environmental pollution so as to improve
production conditions.
</P>
<P>
Sixth, township-run enterprises should be further developed to
absorb surplus rural laborers. Production should be widened and
deepened by developing industries and a service economy and more
small towns and cities built.
</P>
<P>
Seventh, practical measures should be taken to reduce farmers'
burdens. This is of great significance in protecting productive
forces in rural areas and stabilizing the countryside. More should
be given and less taken from farmers.
</P>
<P>
Eighth, China should implement the basic State policy of family
planning. In this respect, both the stress and problem are in the
countryside. Birth control should be advocated in rural areas to
make the rural population adapt to economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
Ninth, development of democratic politics at the grass-roots of
rural areas should be advanced. China should adhere to and improve
the leadership of Party organizations at the grassroots,
strengthen the governments at town and township levels and the
self-government organizations in villages, and safeguard
villagers' right to make decisions by themselves.
</P>
<P>
Tenth, equal attention should be paid to material civilization
and cultural and ethical progress in rurual areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
