<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak-Indian Talks End Without Concrete Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The two sides will continue their discussions on issues of
peace and security and the Kashmir dispute in their next round of
talks to be held February next year in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
The talks beginning from Friday was the first formal encounter
between Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad and his Indian
counterpart K Ragunath after a year-long lapse.
</P>
<P>
During the talks the two sides took up issues of peace and
security and agreed to review the existing confidence building
measures between the two countries in order to enhance their
efficacy.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also held exclusive discussions on the
contentious Kashmir dispute yet made little progress on this
50-year-old issue with both sides reiterating their respective
known positions.
</P>
<P>
Another round of talks will be held in New Delhi from November
5-13 to discuss the remaining bilateral issues of the eight-point
agenda reached by the two countries here last June. 
</P>
