<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen Urges Early Cross-Straits Political Talks (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Qian Qichen, member of the
Political Bureau of the Central Committee Chinese Communist Party,
today urged early political talks between the Chinese mainland and
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Koo Chen-fu and his delegation from the
Straits Exchange Foundation in Taiwan this morning, Qian said
cross-strait political talks are only a matter of time should the
reunification be achieved through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
"Holding such talks is better than not (holding the talks) and
better to hold it at earlier date," said Qian.
</P>
<P>
He extended warm welcome to Koo as head of the delegation to visit
the mainland and to exchange views with the Association of Relations
for Across the Strait.
</P>
<P>
Qian said SEF's visit is of positive significance to improving
the cross-strait relations. The direct meeting between the two
sides not only may remove misunderstandings but also increase
understanding and help reduce differences or bring the two sides
closer at the least.
</P>
<P>
Ending hostility and realising cross-straits direct postal,
commercial and transport links have a direct bearing on the
interests of Taiwan compatriots, Qian said, adding that proper
settlement of these issues not only is the immediate need of the
cross-strait relations, but also entirely comply with the
aspirations of the Taiwan compatriots for peace, stability and for
maintaining the status quo, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
"Taiwan now practises capitalist system and after the
reunification, Taiwan may retain the capitalist system while the
mainland of the motherland practises socialist system," Qian said.
</P>
<P>
"By reunification, we mean to safeguard the state territorial
integrity and sovereignty, not to argue over systems," Qian said.
</P>
<P>
"It is obviously not realistic for some people in Taiwan to
preach that "Taiwan-style democracy" should be the decisive factor
of the reunification," said Qian.
</P>
<P>
He further pointed out under "one China" principle, the
political talks can cover wide-ranging issues, including all the
issues concerned by the Taiwan side. The talks are a long process
during which many problems may be resolved gradually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
