<HEADLINE> EU Allocates $619m for Projects in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Union will
launch 13 different projects and programs in Ethiopia at a cost
of 4.5 billion Birr or 619 million U.S. Dollars in accordance
with the financial protocols of the Lome IV Conventions.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian Herald Sunday quoted Abebaw Feleke, the chief of
the EU desk in the Ethiopian Ministry of Economic Development and
Cooperation, as saying that the EU budget was allocated for the
execution of major projects and programs in the road, water
supply, education, food security, democratization and structural
reform sectors.
</P>
<P>
Abebaw said the largest of these projects involves the
renovation and asphalting of the 335-km Addis Ababa-Jimma road
with a budget of 1.7 billion Birr (223 million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that an aid of 280 million Birr (38.5 million
Dollars) has been obtained based on agreements reached with major
donors for the purchase of educational materials and production
machinery as part of the effort for strengthening the educational
sector development programs.
</P>
<P>
Preparations are being made at a cost of 200 million Birr
(27.5 million Dollars) aimed at building household food security
systems, he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, said the official, the EU has also allocated 80
million Birr (11 million Dollars) for bolstering the capacity of
state administrations and the establishment of human rights and
Ombudsman institutions.
</P>
<P>
The EU is also preparing for strengthening legal and judicial
reform programs and for streamlining the social service reform
program in Ethiopia over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Economic cooperation projects between Ethiopia and the EU are
carried out on the basis of the Lome Convention signed among 71
African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) countries and the 15 member
states of the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
