<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Praised for Helping Iranians' Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Iran has lauded U.N. special
envoy on Afghan affairs Lakhdar Brahimi and the Red Cross for
helping in the release Iranians held by the Afghan Taliban, the
official news agency IRNA reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi has expressed
appreciation for the efforts by Brahimi and the Red Cross
following the release of 26 Iranians in captivity.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi also said that the attitude of Iranian government
towards the Taliban would depend on their fulfillment of
international expectations from them.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-six freed Iranians returned here Saturday evening in two
Red Cross planes after Brahimi secured a promise from Taliban
leaders during a visit to Kandahar, the militia's headquarters in
southern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Brahimi would re-visit Tehran Tuesday for
further talks with Iranian officials after the Taliban's
announced readiness to negotiate with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy has been shuttling in the region in an effort to
to defuse the tension between Iran and the Taliban, set off by the
Taliban's killing in August of nine Iranian diplomats and reporter
in Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
