<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: What Prompts Devaluation of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi taka, the country's
currency, was depreciated by 2.97 percent against the U.S. dollar
on Sunday following an announcement of the central Bangladesh Bank
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The new buying and selling rates between the Bangladesh Bank
and the authorized banks were 48.356 taka and 48.65 taka
respectively, and the buying-selling middle rate rose to 48.50
taka from the previous 47.10 taka.
</P>
<P>
This is the second devaluation of the taka since the current
1998-99 fiscal year began on July 1, and the 14th since the ruling
Awami League came to power in June, 1996, raising the price of a
dollar by 6.75 taka from 41.75 taka to 48.50 taka. It is also the
highest one so far in the 1990s in a single go.
</P>
<P>
The taka continued to remain "one of the most stable currencies
in the region" and the adjustment was necessary to "spur growth of
exports while retaining its competitive edge," considering the
recent domestic and external influences on the external sector
position of Bangladesh, the Bangladesh Bank said, referring to the
over-two-month-long flood and the financial crisis originating
last year in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Hossain Zilllur Rahman, an economist at Bangladesh Institute of
Development Studies, said the depreciation would make imports
expensive while easing the exports to some extent.
</P>
<P>
"But it was not clear why the government went for the
devaluation, as there had been no compelling grounds or reasons
for such massive adjustment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Financial analysts here also doubted the rationale the bank
cited for the devaluation when the Real Effective Exchange Rate
(REER) and the Nominal Effective Exchange Rate stood at their
comfortable levels below 100, and the country's exports showed
upward trend in earnings during the first two months of the
current fiscal year while imports kept declining.
</P>
<P>
They said the latest devaluation indicated that the government,
ignoring the REER signal, had taken such a step under pressure.
</P>
<P>
The REER is an index prepared everyday by the Bangladesh Bank
reflecting the changes in the exchange rate of taka and inflation
rates vis-a-vis the currencies of Bangladesh's major trading
partners under a trade-weighted basket.
</P>
<P>
The taka comes pressure if the REER Index crosses the
100-level. The government has pursued a policy of mini-adjustment
in the exchange rate of taka in the past few years, based on
changes in the REER.
</P>
<P>
A report in Sunday's edition of The Financial Express said the
decision of devaluation was made immediately after the meeting of
Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria with the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) in Washington earlier this month. Some high
officials of the central bank also felt surprised at having such
big devaluation, it added.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference last Monday, Kibria said the government
would get 130 million dollars from the IMF for balance of payment
support to meet its import needs, and relevant agreements would be
signed within this month or next month.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh would not be able to get the money free, but under
some conditionalities, according to the analysts. One of the
conditions was the devaluation of the taka, they said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has long been pressing Bangladesh to make further
devaluation of the taka against the dollar, arguing that the
country's southeastern Asian competitors have all devalued their
currencies between 50 and 80 percent in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The analysts noted that the depreciation itself could not
improve much the external competitiveness of the economy if not
synchronized by actions particularly in areas of fiscal and
monetary policies.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, as the country depends heavily on imports of light
industrial products and raw materials for its flourishing
export-oriented garment industry, the devaluation would surely
raise the import cost, they said.
</P>
<P>
A devaluation made on pressure, instead of aimed at maintaining
a "correct real exchange rate" of the currency, would undoubtedly
hurt the national economy seriously, causing possible inflation,
they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
