<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Ruling Coalition Parties Directed to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 18 (Xinhua) -- All component parties of
Malaysia's the ruling Barisan Nasional (BN) (National Front)
coalition have been directed to immediately activate their
respective election machinery to guarantee no erosion to the
coalition's massive majority in the next general election.
</P>
<P>
The directive was issued by BN Secretary-General Mohamed
Rahmat, who is the information minister, in Johor Baharu Saturday
night, the Malaysian national news agency Bernama reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed called upon all BN component parties, the backbone
United Malays National Organization (UMNO) in particular, to
intensify efforts to endear themselves to the masses and keep the
people enlightened on the current political problems. The
political problems were clearly referred to the sacking of Deputy
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim and the events occurred thereafter.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed hoped all 14 BN components were now in a high level of
preparedness and would have by now taken care of internal problems
besides avoiding quarrels over seat allocation and candidates.
</P>
<P>
He said after its landslide victory in the 1995 general
election, a reduced majority could not be ruled out for the BN in
the next polls "but the decline would not be to extent of the BN
government being defeated". He expressed confidence that the
present government will be re-elected and continue to enjoy
support."
</P>
<P>
"UMNO is still solid and strong and so are the BN components,"
he said, adding BN components have repeatedly expressed support
for Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad's actions as BN chairman.
</P>
<P>
The opposition in the country publicly stated its objective of
eroding away the BN's two-thirds majority in the next polls, which
Mohamed described as "a dream".
</P>
<P>
The next general election is due to be held in April 2000, but
an early general election was recently much talked about. 
</P>
</TEXT>
