<HEADLINE> Pakistan, India Open Final Session of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The Foreign Secretaries of
Pakistan and India entered into the final session of the on-going
peace talks between the two South Asian arch-rivals here Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad and his Indian
counterpart K Ragunath started their talks for the third day at
around 11:30 a.m. local time Sunday at a government guest house
here.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad told reporters before stepping into the conference
room that the fact that Pakistan and India resumed their
high-level dialogue after a 13-month break was a "major progress".
</P>
<P>
He said both Islamabad and New Delhi are ready to address the
outstanding issues between them "seriously" as they have realized
that the two countries' development are left far behind the other
countries because their 50-year old tensions.
</P>
<P>
The current talks are being held in a "frank and cordial"
manner and the two sides are cool and calm, he said.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad and Ragunath have already held discussions on issues
of peace and security and the contentious Kashmir dispute during
the Friday and Saturday's intense talks.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are expected to issue a joint statement at the
end of Sunday's session, which will spell out the timing of their
next round of talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
