<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 07:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Starts Crackdown on Illegal Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti security forces
arrested about 300 illegal resident Saturday on the first day of a
crackdown following a one-month amnesty, Interior Ministry sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The sources, quoted by the local English daily Arab Times,
said the crackdown focused on the main expatriate concentrations
in the capital city of Kuwait, the industrial Shuwaikh area,
Kheitan, Juleeb, Al-Shuyoukh and Fahaheel.
</P>
<P>
The crackdown will continue in the coming days, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry had granted illegal residents a one-month
amnesty to leave the country without paying fine or legalize their
stay.
</P>
<P>
The grace period expired last Wednesday although some illegals
were allowed to leave on Thursday. Thursday and Friday are public
holidays here according to local custom.
</P>
<P>
The ministry estimated that over 11,000 illegal residents were
in Kuwait before the start of amnesty. It is not known exactly how
many of them have left, but unconfirmed reports put the figure at
3,000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many of the overstayers have legalized their stays
after the amnesty was issued, said a ministry official.
</P>
<P>
The ministry sources said that all those arrested will be
deported and banned from return, while those who left during the
amnesty are free to come back after obtaining a new work visa.
</P>
<P>
The small Gulf country is very much in need of all kinds of
foreign labor. Of a population of about 2.2 million in Kuwait,
two-thirds are expatriates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
