<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 1000 Students Enter Delhi University With Fake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Over 1000 students are
suspected to have secured admission to various colleges of Delhi
University this year with forged documents, the Times of India
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Delhi Police Crime Branch said they had arrested three persons,
believed to have been involved in preparing and selling the fake
documents, and the racket may have been operating in the garb of
coaching institutes.
</P>
<P>
The Delhi University registrar had been requested to get the
documents of all students admitted this year verified within one
week from either the Central Bureau of Secondary Education or the
crime branch.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the crime branch said Saturday that a large number
of students and their parents, who obtained admission on the basis
of such documents were likely to be arrested in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
During their investigation, the police scrutinized 1,100
admission forms of students admitted to Shivaji College of the
Delhi University and found that 82 students, 10 of them girls, had
been admitted on the basis of forged documents.
</P>
<P>
In a trap laid by the police, said the Times of India, a decoy
customer met with one of the suspects in the case named
Jaiprakash, who run a private coaching center in Delhi, and agreed
to pay him 10,000 rupees (some 250 U.S. dollars) for three
documents including marksheet, character certificate and
school-leaving certificate.
</P>
<P>
A police team raided the Alpha Public School run by the suspect
and caught him red-handed with the three documents ordered by the
decoy customer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Three Goals for Agricultural, Rural Development (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 18 (Xinhua) -- China puts forward three major
goals for building new socialist rural areas with Chinese
characteristics between now and 2010, according to a decision of
the ruling Communist Party of China (CPC) released here today.
</P>
<P>
The "Decision of the CPC Central Committee on Several Major
Issues in the Development of Agriculture and Rural Work" was
adopted at the Third Plenum of the 15th CPC Central Committee on
October 14, 1998 in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The decision says: the country should adhere to the domination
by public ownership while developing diverse forms of ownership
and emancipating and developing productive forces in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
An effort needs to be made to build a rural economic system
based on the household contract responsibility system, supported
by a socialized service network, a market system for farm produce,
based on the importance placed by the central government on
agriculture so as to adapt to developing a socialist market
economy, the decision says.
</P>
<P>
China should make progress in improving agricultural science
and technology, equipment, and productive forces. Farm produce
supplies should meet the needs of national economic development,
population growth and improved living standards, it adds.
</P>
<P>
The rural industrial structure needs to be further optimized,
and big progress is made in urbanization, with increases in
farmers' incomes to give them an affluent life, it says.
</P>
<P>
Politically, the decision points out, the leadership of the
Communist Party of China should be upheld, socialist democratic
politics strengthened, democracy at grass-roots units expanded,
and the rights of Chinese farmers' to exercise democracy in
accordance with the law guaranteed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Three Goals for Agricultural, Rural Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Township governments need to be kept small in size but are
highly efficient, the decision says, adding that village
organizations with Party branches as the core should be
strengthened, relationships between officials and the villagers be
closer, the pace of a rule by law increased, and good social order
security environment maintained in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Culturally, it cont9inues, the nation should promote socialist
culture and ethics in rural areas, train a new type of farmers
with lofty ideals, moral integrity, good education and a strong
sense of discipline.
</P>
<P>
Ideological and moral education should be intensified, healthy
social conduct advocateded, education developed, nine-year
compulsary education system obligatory, illiteracy wiped out, and
scientific and technical know-how spread, it says.
</P>
<P>
Rural public healthy and sports should be given priority,
farmers made aware of elementary hygiene, more cultural facilities
built, and rural cultural life enriched, it added.
</P>
<P>
China's primary stage of socialism is a underdeveloped stage,
especially in rural areas, it points out. This means that the
country should take economic development and improving
agricultural productive forces should be the central task of the
rural economy. All policies should help boosting the economic
vitality in rural areas. The farmers should be relied on to
transform the backwardness. The standards of farmers' material and
cultural life should be improved.
</P>
<P>
The basic guiding principles for development in the primary
stage of socialism and the tasks for the first decade of the next
century laid down at the 15th Party Congress pointed the way out
to the modernization of China's agriculture and rural areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
