<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Undertake Environmental Rehabilitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi Ministry of
Forest and Environment has proposed a post-flood environment
rehabilitation program with a cost of over 1.1 billion taka (about
2.27 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
This proposal is made on the basis of a study report on the
assessment of environmental impacts of flood, 1998, prepared by
the Department of Environment with the aid of the UNDP (United
Nations Development program), a daily reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The study report would assess the damage inflicted to the
lives, property and environment by the century's worst flood, The
Independent quoted Minister of Forest and Environment Sajeda
Chowdhury as saying.
</P>
<P>
This is for the first time that a comprehensive study has been
undertaken to identify the areas of damage to the environment
after the devastating flood, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The study report was prepared by a group of experts, and it
would be of an immense help in the planning of pre- and post flood
preparedness and rehabilitation program after flood, she observed.
</P>
<P>
It would also help lessen the damage of the flood in future and
specific suggestion would be provided in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The recent severe flood has caused an irreparable damage to the
forest resources of the country, she said, adding that the total
loss has been estimated at above 1.1 billion taka (about 2.27
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The reconstruction of roads and other works of infrastructural
development are going on in full swing, and every effort has been
made to restore the normal pace of development activities in
environmental sector, she noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
