<HEADLINE> OSCE Advance Team Arrives in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRISTINA, Yugoslavia, October 18 (Xinhua) -- A half dozen OSCE
technical experts arrived in the Kosovo capital of Pristina
Saturday evening to begin preparing for a 2,000-strong
verification mission in the southern Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
The mission of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe is designed to ensure Yugslav President Slobodan Milosevic
complies fully with U.N. Security Council Resolution 1199, passed
on September 23, which demands an immediate ceasefire, a
withdrawal of Serbian forces from Kosovo, a return of refugees and
autonomy talks with the province's ethnic Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
The team consists of representatives of the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe's secretariat, of member
countries of the Contact Group for former Yugoslavia (Britain,
France, Germany, Italy, Russia and the United States), and Norway
and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
A further 150 members were expected to arrive in Kosovo "in the
next two weeks", said an OSCE spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
