<HEADLINE> Hurricane Lester Prompts Mexican Exodus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Civil protection personnel
are rushing ahead of hurricane Lester to evacuate thousands of
residents in the southern Mexican states of Oaxaca and Guerrero,
reports said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In Oaxaca, authorities have started to alert the population
through radio and television messages, aiming to reduce potential
damage to be resulted from the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
A hurricane in early September hit the southeastern state of
Chiapas, killing 200 people and affecting 400,000 others.
</P>
<P>
Civil protection organizations are in a state of alert in
Oaxaca because Lester has changed course again and could lash the
coast of Puerto Angel and Pinotepa Nacional in the state.
</P>
<P>
At least 650 families have been evacuated from areas believed
to bear high risks.
</P>
<P>
Guerrero state authorities have prepared 114 refuges for 10,000
residents.
</P>
<P>
At 13:30 local time (18:30 GMT), Lester was 120 kilometers (75
miles) south of Huatulco, Oaxaca, and was moving west-northwest at
11 kilometers (6.8 miles) per hour.
</P>
<P>
The hurricane develops winds of more than 160 kilometers (100
miles) per hour, with gusts of up to 190 kilometers (120 miles)
per hour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
