<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Says Pinochet's Arrest Violates Diplomatic Immunity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Chile said on Saturday the
detention of its former military leader Augusto Pinochet in London
was in violation of diplomatic immunity.
</P>
<P>
According to a communique from the Chilean Foreign Affairs
Ministry, Pinochet was traveling with a diplomatic passport in his
capacity as a senator-for-life.
</P>
<P>
The former commander-in-chief of the Chilean army, convalescing
in a London clinic after minor surgery, was detained earlier
Saturday on the request of Spanish courts probing alleged
organized killing of Spanish citizens in Chile between 1973 and
1990 when Pinochet ran the country.
</P>
<P>
Chilean Foreign Minister Jose Miguel Insulza expressed regret
at Pinochet's detention at a press conference in the Portuguese
city of Oporto, where he was accompanying President Eduardo Frei
at an Ibero-American Summit.
</P>
<P>
Insulza said the matter "is particularly deplorable" as it
"impinges on our political process and our relations with other
states."
</P>
<P>
"I do not believe that this could be anybody's plot or out of
political motivation on the part of the British or Spanish
governments," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chilean government would seek an early settlement
of the issue through political and judicial ways. "Our only
possible road is to have immunity validated," he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that his country is against
extra-territorial laws and that Chileans could only be tried by
Chilean courts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
