<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 44th CPA Conference opens in Wellington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The 44th Conference of the
Commonwealth Parliamentary Association (CPA) opened in Wellington
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Governor-General Sir Michael Hardie Boys, Prime
Minister Jenny Shipley, Commonwealth Secretary-General Chief Emeka
Anyaoku, and about 500 senior parliamentarians and parliamentary
officials from more than 50 countries attended the opening
session, which was presided over by CPA president Doug Kidd.
</P>
<P>
The five-day conference is scheduled to discuss issues on
globalization and its impact on Commonwealth governments and
parliaments.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Shipley delivered a low-keynote speech at the
opening session, saying the conference's theme is "both complex
and potentially controversial".
</P>
<P>
"The onset of globalization, where markets, information and
ideas flow seamlessly across national borders, is already having a
direct impact on governments and parliaments. Realistically the
trend will intensify in the future," Shipley said.
</P>
<P>
"People will know more but feel less secure. Electorates the
world over will embrace the new icons of international culture but
will worry about how to retain local and indigenous traditions and
values. The international financial institutions, set up after
World War II, are and will struggle to keep pace with the impact
of global capital flows. Many millions of people, including those
around the Asia Pacific Basin, who have experienced such economic
and social improvement in the last 15 years, have in the last 15
months seen their expectations of rising incomes and economic
security replaced by the fear and anxiety concerning poverty and
unemployment," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced there is no single policy prescription that
will ensure growth, development and equity in every Commonwealth
country. We can learn from each other. We each have to find what
suits and works for us given our own circumstances," Mrs Shipley
said.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister said her Government is committed to pursuing
"an open and internationally competitive economy" and her country
needs "sustainable non-inflationary economic and employment
growth" to finance its social spending and infrastructural
investment.
</P>
<P>
In her speech, she conveyed to the attendants the New Zealand
Government's decision to endorse its Minister of Foreign Affairs
and Trade Don McKinnon as a candidate to succeed Chief Anyaoku as
the Secretary-General of the Commonwealth at the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
McKinnon is leading the New Zealand delegation to the
conference.  
</P>
</TEXT>
