<HEADLINE> Brazil Expects Harvest Growth in 1998-1999 Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Brazil is expected to produce
85 million metric tons of cereal, legumes and oil-bearing seeds in
the next crop season, up 7.6 percent from this year.
</P>
<P>
The latest projection, provided by Brazilian Agriculture
Minister Francisco Turra, was confirmed by Eugenio Stephanello,
president of Brazil's National Supplies Company.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Turra said, the country's harvests of beans, corn
and rice are also likely to go up by 5, 12 and 15 percent
respectively in the 1998-1999 season.
</P>
<P>
By estimation, Brazil will have to spend two billion
U.S. dollars this year to import 9.5 million tons of grains needed
by the domestic food market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
