<HEADLINE> Indonesian President to Attend APEC Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie had decided to attend the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation Forum (APEC) summit in Malaysia next month, a
government official said.
</P>
<P>
The president made this decision because he was encouraged by
Malaysian authorities' better treatment of former Malaysian deputy
prime minister Anwar Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
"The better treatment given to Anwar and a possible house
arrest status for him have eradicated major barriers for the
visit," Presidential Spokeswoman Dewi Fortuna Anwar told the
Jakarta Post on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Anwar has transferred from the Bukit Aman
federal police headquarters in Kuala Lumpur to the modern Sungai
Buloh prison.
</P>
<P>
The summit was also strategically very important for the
region, she added.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta Post Saturday quoted a reliable source as saying
that Habibie had assured Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad
during a recent telephone conversation that he would attend the
APEC summit in Kuala Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
"Habibie told Mahathir that he did not intend to interfere in
Malaysia's internal affairs, he was just worried about the
condition of his close friend Anwar," a palace official who spoke
on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The official said Habibie telephoned Mahathir shortly before
his meeting with Philippine President Joseph Estrada in Batam near
Singapore on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Habibie told the prime minister he had to drop his planned
visit to Kuala Lumpur on October 9 due to his mounting domestic
duties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
