<DOCNO> XIE19981018.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Claims Preventing Heroin from Reaching U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar claimed that it has
prevented 45 billion U.S. dollars worth of heroin from reaching
streets of the United States since 1988 up to date despite cut in
assistance by the U.S. since then.
</P>
<P>
In a latest report on the political situation of Myanmar,
issued by the Office of Strategic Studies of the Defense Ministry,
the government blamed the U.S. and the Western World for not only
refusing to recognize and encourage Myanmar's efforts in the fight
against narcotic drugs, but also putting obstacles in the move by
imposing an arms embargo.
</P>
<P>
The drug armies use sophisticated weapons to fight against the
government, while the government troops use weapons of inferior
quality, inflicting heavy casualties.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that the Myanmar government had managed
to break the notorious drug army of khun Sa in the Golden Triangle
area and had him surrender unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
The for/2De5rug warlord Khun Sa and his 15,000-strong Mong Tai
Army laid down their arms in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
During the 14-year period between 1974 and 1988, Myanmar has
cooperated with the U.S. in anti-narcotic operations, obtaining
an aid of 68 million dollars from the U.S. side. The aid was
provided mainly for training Myanmar officials and for the use of
spare parts and equipment in drug eradication operations, the
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
