<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Japan to Take More Steps for World Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 17 (Xinhua) - U.S. President Bill Clinton
Saturday urged Japan to take more steps to help improve world
economic growth by opening and deregulating its economy.
</P>
<P>
In a weekly radio address, Clinton said Japan, the world's
second-largest economy behind the United States, must open and
deregulate its economy to strengthen its financial system.
</P>
<P>
"Now it's critical to avoid further delay by moving quickly and
using that money most effectively ... Now the health of Asia's
economy -- and indeed the world -- depends upon Japan," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I welcome the substantial assistance in Japan's legislation to
repair its troubled banking system."
</P>
<P>
He said America's prosperity is inextricably tied to markets
overseas, and "we stand ready to help countries that develop
policies to keep their economy strong."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said it was critical for Asia and Europe to promote
growth to prevent new global financial turmoil and protect
American prosperity.
</P>
<P>
He also heralded the newly approved U.S. contribution of 17.9
billion U.S. dollars to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) as
"an insurance policy for our own economy."
</P>
<P>
"Now the IMF is stronger and ready to act. We must make
certain that when it acts, it acts to promote global growth and to
limit the reach of financial crisis. In turn, this will foster a
stronger economy here at home and help our own workers, farmers
and ranchers," he added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's remarks came two days after the U.S. Federal Reserve,
in a surprise move, cut key lending rates by a quarter percentage
point for the second time within three weeks.
</P>
<P>
The White House and Congress agreed earlier this week to free
up the emergency fund for the IMF as part of the federal budget
deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
