<HEADLINE> Economic Crisis Affects Thailand's private Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BANGKOK, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The economic crisis has taken
its toll on Thailand's privately-run educational establishments
with over 1,800 million baht (45 million U.S. dollars) in delayed
payments of tuition fees, according to the Office of the Private
Education Commission.
</P>
<P>
the Commission was quoted Sunday by the Bangkok Post as saying
that many private colleges and schools have been suffering from
the liquidity crunch this year due to uncollected tuition fees.
</P>
<P>
The amount of delayed tuition fees rose sharply to 1,889
million baht (47.2 million U.S. dollars) this year against 517
million baht (12.9 million U.S. dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
In private-owned secondary schools, 404,252 students have not
yet paid 1,085 million baht (27.1 million U.S. dollars) in tuition
fees to schools.
</P>
<P>
At the college level, 129,000 students owe 804 million baht
(20.1 million U.S. dollars) in tuition fees to colleges, the
commission said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
