<HEADLINE> Southgate: England Persecuted by Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 17 (Xinhua) -- England manager Glenn Hoddle
has condemned reports of a dressing room mutiny following
England's midweek match in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed the story, carried in The Sun newspaper, as a
"vicious lie" and defender Gareth Southgate said the team felt
persecuted by the media.
</P>
<P>
Hoddle said he was beginning to believe what he had been told
that there were "people out there" trying to undermine his job.
</P>
<P>
A front page story in Saturday's Sun newspaper said an angry
confrontation came after Hoddle had demanded an explanation of
the team's poor performance in Wednesday's 3-0 European
championship qualifier win over Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Hoddle, under fire for the side's miserable form since the
World Cup finals, was quoted as saying: "No-one leaves this
dressing room until you tell me why you are producing
performances like this."
</P>
<P>
Shearer was reported to have snapped back: "Have you ever
thought it might be down to you."
</P>
<P>
Hoddle said the suggestion that he and his captain had had a
row was "just mischievous, pure garbage".
</P>
<P>
But he admitted he had "a pop" at the team during halftime in
Luxembourg and that there had been a frank exchange of views
after the match.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very disappointed over these vicious lies," said Hoddle.
"I have spoken to Alan Shearer and he can't believe it.
</P>
<P>
"People are going out of their way to invent stories...some of
the garbage is laughable."
</P>
<P>
He said the flak he had been receiving would serve only to
make him more determined to ensure that England "do well and
qualify for the European championship finals".
</P>
<P>
Southgate, who scored England's third goal on Wednesday night,
said he was "amused and bemused" by what was written.
</P>
<P>
"I thought I must have been in a different dressing room quite
frankly," he told BBC radio.
</P>
<P>
"As far as I am aware there was nothing out of the ordinary on
Wednesday night," he added.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the players were convinced that some people were
out to "get" the coach, he said:
</P>
<P>
"Yes, I think we are convinced that people are out to get
everybody, quite honestly."
</P>
<P>
British Sports Minister Tony Banks said it was time the fans
and media got behind Hoddle.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone thinks they know how to pick a winning team,"Banks
told BBC radio. "The trouble is the people with these opinions
are usually propping up bars or writing newspaper columns.
</P>
<P>
"It is all about results. If he (Hoddle) gets results then
obviously everyone thinks he is going to walk on water and does
walk on water. If he doesn't they will want to drown him in it.It
is an impossible job."  
</P>
</TEXT>
