<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, October 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN -- Germany's Social Democratic Party (SPD) and the Greens
said Saturday that they have successfully wound up 10 days of
negotiations on a common policy platform and will sign the deal to
form a coalition government next week.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a final round of policy negotiations, the SPD and
Greens said that they would spend the next few days to finalize
the distribution of cabinet posts before formally signing a
coalition contract next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The center-left SPD, which has been in opposition for 16 years,
defeated Chancellor Helmut Kohl's conservative alliance in general
elections on September 27. It needs to form a coalition government
with the ecologist Greens in order to muster a stable majority in
parliament. (BC-SPD-Greens-Coalition)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton Saturday met Israeli
and Palestinian leaders to try to mediate differences over
security issues which are blocking the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived at the Wye Plantation, Maryland, by helicopter
from Washington for meetings with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
After two days of negotiations, diplomatic sources said that
key security issues remained unsettled while Netanyahu and Arafat
exchanged allegations Friday that suggest mistrust between the two
leaders persists.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was trying to clear the way for an agreement by Sunday,
the end of four days of talks, but signs of discord were
evident. (BC-US-Mideast-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- A group of 26 Iranians released by the Afghan Taliban
militia arrived here Saturday evening, the official news agency
IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
These Iranians, mainly truck drivers, were set free by the
Taliban following the mediation of Lakhdar Brahimi, special envoy
of the U.N. secretary general on Afghan affairs.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi has visited Iran, Pakistan and Afghanistan in an effort
to defuse the tension between Iran and the Taliban, triggered by
the killing of nine Iranian diplomats and reporter by the Taliban
forces in August.
</P>
<P>
Iran massed more than 200,000 troops on its eastern border with
Afghanistan to put pressure to bear on the Taliban, the student
militia now controlling 90 percent of the
country. (BC-Iran-Taliban-Released)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The disputed Kuril Islands was among the top items
discussed here Saturday by Russian and Japanese foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
"The territorial question was obviously discussed as an
integral part of a peace treaty," Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov told reporters after his talks with his Japanese
counterpart, Masahiko Komura.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said the issue "should be settled without damaging
Russia's sovereignty and territorial integrity."
</P>
<P>
Komura arrived here Friday night on a trip designated to make
preparations for Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's upcoming
state visit to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The visit, scheduled for November 10-13, will be the first
official state visit to Russia by a Japanese Prime Minister in 25
years. (BC-Russia-Japan-Visit) 
</P>
