<HEADLINE> Pak, China Sign Telecommunications Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 17 (Xinhua) -- A 95 million dollars
telecommunications contract was signed here Saturday between
Pakistan Telecommunication Company Limited (PTCL) and China Wanbo
Engineering Corporation and Zhongxing Telecom Ltd. (a Consortium).
</P>
<P>
This includes a turnkey contract for supply and installation of
266,000 digital telephone lines covering Pakistan's 15 major
cities, according to a press release issued by the PTCL in the
signing ceremony held Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the above contract, agreements also signed at
the same time include technology transfer, local manufacturing,
loan of 35 million dollars and future commitment of financing of
40 million dollars for the next five years at most favorable
financing terms, said the release.
</P>
<P>
While introducing new switches, the release said that the PTCL
is ensuring that new technology integrates satisfactorily with its
existing network.
</P>
<P>
For this purpose two trial exchanges are being commissioned in
the southern port city of Karachi and Islamabad within next three
months. On satisfactory integration balance replacement and new
lines will be commissioned countryside.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract, the Chinese Consortium has committed to
hold the prices of all items supplied in the contract for five
years for future orders on two percent interest and dollar
deferred financing terms.
</P>
<P>
With the implementation of these agreements the
telecommunication infrastructure will be expanded rapidly, said
the release.
</P>
<P>
The reduced prices will help PTCL in installation of more lines
and quickly bridge the demand and supply gap within the available
resources, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
