<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's SPD, Greens to Seal Coalition Deal Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Social Democratic Party
(SPD) and the Greens said Saturday that they have successfully
wound up 10 days of negotiations on a common policy platform and
will sign the deal to form a coalition government next week.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a final round of policy negotiations, the SPD and
Greens said that they would spend the next few days to finalize
the distribution of cabinet posts before formally signing a
coalition contract next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The center-left SPD, which has been in opposition for 16 years,
defeated Chancellor Helmut Kohl's conservative alliance in general
elections on September 27. It needs to form a coalition government
with the ecologist Greens in order to muster a stable majority in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, the two parties reached a deal to raise the
country's energy tax.
</P>
<P>
Petrol prices would be increased by 0.06 German marks (0.04
U.S. dollars) per Liter from January next year. Meanwhile prices
for heating oil, natural gas and electricity would also be raised.
</P>
<P>
The extra revenues would be used to finance a 0.8 percent cut
in non-wage labor costs which include mandatory payments for
health and unemployment insurance, officials of two parties said.
</P>
<P>
The SPD and Greens on Saturday also reached a compromise on the
transportation policy with the Greens dropping its demand for a
general speed limit on the country's highways.
</P>
<P>
Separately, Rudolf Scharping, the SPD's current parliamentary
leader who would become Germany's defense minister, confirmed
Saturday that the German armed forces would remain at its current
strength of 340,000 soldiers and would not face further cuts in
defense budget soon as demanded by the Greens.
</P>
<P>
During the past weeks, the SPD and Greens already reache d
agreement on a wide range of policy issues, including foreign
policy and a tax reform.
</P>
<P>
With the coalition package now complete, both the SPD and
Greens will hold a party convention at the end of next week to
approve the deal. The new government is due to be sworn in at the
end of this month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
