<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Links Mild acne to Depression, Suicide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, October 17 (Xinhua) -- A new study shows that even
mild acne can be associated with such emotional problems as
significant clinical depression and even suicide, the American
Counseling Association (ACA) reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted by Madhulika Gupta, a professor at the
University of Western Ontario, Canada, who presented her findings
at a recent meeting in San Francisco. Gupta said that "the
cosmetic impact of even mild acne can cause a profound emotional
burden for some young people."
</P>
<P>
According to ACA, the world's private organization for
professional counselors, acne is often a source of embarrassment
and anxiety to teenagers, and this new study confirms the
importance of seeking treatment of teenage skin conditions sooner
rather than later.
</P>
<P>
Gupta and her colleagues found that the prevalence of
depression and suicidal thinking among patients with mild to
moderate acine was similar to that among patients suffering from
moderately severe psoriasis, a far more chronic and cosmetically
disfiguring condition.
</P>
<P>
According to Gupta, a psychiatrist who studies the
psychological effects of skin problems, the effects of acne may be
expressed in a number of ways, including low-esteem and social
withdrawal and lifestyle limitations. She urged parents to seek
medical treatment for their teenagers who have acne.
</P>
<P>
Acne is a disease that affects about 17 million people in the
United States, and nearly 80 percent of the population will
develop some form of acne during their lifetime time, ACA said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
