<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Mediates Palestine-Israel Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Saturday met Israeli and Palestinian leaders to try to mediate
differences over security issues which are blocking the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived at the Wye Plantation, Maryland, by helicopter
from Washington for meetings with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
After two days of negotiations, diplomatic sources said that
key security issues remained unsettled while Netanyahu and Arafat
exchanged allegations Friday that suggest mistrust between the two
leaders persists.
</P>
<P>
At the Wye Plantation, Clinton met and had lunch with senior
U.S. officials and then had a 90-minute meeting with Arafat. Then
the president telephoned a report to President Hosni Mubarak of
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Later Clinton had a meeting with Netanyahu at River House, a
luxurious estate overlooking the Wye River. Six aides, including
George Tenet of the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), from
the U.S. and Israel participated in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was trying to clear the way for an agreement by Sunday,
the end of four days of talks, but signs of discord were evident.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the venue, White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart gave a terse account that made no reference to the
disputed topics.
</P>
<P>
"We think the environment out here has provided the ability for
informal discussions and has provided an atmosphere that is
constructive," Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
He said Clinton enjoyed a "strong reservoir of trust" with the
two leaders, and if he can play "a constructive role," the
president will return Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's talks were being described as "informal" since it is
the Jewish Sabbath and work is proscribed.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has agreed to relinquish a further 13 percent of the
West Bank, with 3 percent designated as a nature preserve, but has
declared there will be no agreement unless Arafat takes concrete
steps to curb terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The summit is meant to break a 19-month stalemate in the peace
process by nailing down a new transfer of land to the Palestinians
in the West Bank in return for cast-iron Palestinian guarantees
they will crack down on militants.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said some working groups were meeting for a
third day and that Clinton's participation means a new sense of
urgency.
</P>
<P>
The first two days had essentially been a review of positions,
many of which are still far apart, and they were waiting for U.S.
proposals to breathe life into the talks, which Washington wants
to end by Monday at the latest.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
